\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}
}Florence{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Ethel. Mary. Of all names. When I was a little girl - I was taken to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Isle of Wight{\*\xmlclose}. So a gentleman asked me my name. I was only four. 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Florence{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} Ethel Mary - Miss Dart. You know, it lived with me all my life. And all the family always kept that up, with me, Miss Dart, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You moved from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Chatham{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 To - Southsea. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And you were only a few months old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, I was only a few months old when I went there first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And then you moved from Southsea to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} when you were five years old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. In - that was in 1900.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 So you were born in 1895.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 95. So I was five years old when I came here. My father came to Portl
and - before he - he was on the Igeria - and he came to Portland before he came to the dockyard, he wanted to see what he was coming into, and he was till in the Navy, he hadn't retired from the Navy then, so - he came to see what was doing you see before
 he came to his job. He was coming through {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Victory Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, then called Drunkards Row, now called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Victory Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and three old Portlanders stopped him. They asked him who he was. So he told them, and they said, well get out, as we don't want none of you be stra
ngers in this place. My mother was here - a short while and - in Fortuneswell there was a very old man keeping a - greengrocers shop. You went down the steps into the shop. But he always had fresh - vegetables, which mother made for. And the first time we
 went in there he said, you can get out. So mother says, yes I will when you serve me. I'll none of you - serve none of you b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11276250\charrsid7023924 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924  strangers, we can do without all you. That was the sort of reception you got - years ago.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this because you were connected with the Navy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, because you were strangers. Strangers, yes. The island - before - 1900 was very conservative, was very - kept in, you didn't - if you married outside well you - comm - committed a great sin. You must marry in the island. Conseque
ntly the - big rate of - mental disease and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
In fact there were a lot of people moving into Underhill to work in the dockyard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 There were a fair number of strangers here in those days weren't there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. They came - a lo
t of that nonsense broke up quite quickly - after 1900 because there was so many coming in you see. There was all the men building the - breakwater and - all - different families coming in. So that - nonsense really -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 But this was the reception that your family got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh that was just - yes, you got when you came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You say your father was still in the Navy at that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, that time, yes. But he came - ashore you see to see what the dockyard was like, what he was going into, because he
 knew he was coming to this dockyard. He'd been appointed there. So he came ashore from the Igeria - to see what it was like, and that was the reception he got. And I've heard him say, that if you went into a public house - and there was some good old Por
tlanders there, good old quarries - you didn't get a very good reception. So all - a lot of that nonsense, it's gone now, there's too many outsiders - here now. There was some very very queer customs - kept up amongst the Portlanders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 For instance?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well you mustn't marry outside the island, it was wrong to marry outside the island. If somebody died you wore black for - endless ages. And you had a big party - for a funeral. Yes. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Your father worked at the dockyard here then until he retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Until he died my dear, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 He wasn't in the Navy then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no, he was out of the Navy, yes. He - he died in 1911.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 That's only eleven years after you came here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 L9 - wait a minute, no - yes, that's wrong. That's my gr
andmother's - the - my grandmother died. What year did he die? Oh, 19 - oh it doesn't matter anyway. He was fifty-one anyway when he died. He died quite young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 He was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Chief carpenter's mate. And in the dockyard he was Target Master.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Have you any idea how old he was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
He was fifty-one when he died. And I was sixteen then. No, he didn't marry very young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Where did he originate from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}
}Plymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Mm. And mother from Sidmouth. Oh yes, all West Country. We're more West Country than anything else. I'm not a - I'm not a Portlander, I'm a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Kimberley{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. You know what that is don't you. Yes, oh yes, you'll be a Kimberler. You did, yes. Yes. This way. Swanage. Yes. Hence - I think - now that's a modern - I think you've been
 given the modern version. There is a much older - meaning. Years ago, now this is - 'course it's only hearsay to me, years ago you couldn't come a - into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} by bridge or - you had to come across by water you see before this bridge was built. And - t
he story is that - there was a number of people on this island living - fairly rough, but some of them are called - Cumben and so on, and one day a number of men were seen coming across the - channel, coming across the water there, in small boats. And whe
n they got near - they called these people on the island who were bending - forward Cumben. Hence the new - hence the surname Cumben. Cumben. Hence the name Cumben.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father go straight in the Navy, or did he have any other jobs?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Went in 
as a boy. And of course had the hard life in the Navy. The hard life of bully beef and - biscuits you see. They used to go - my father went abroad for several commissions, 'cos they weren't two year commissions, they were four year commissions - in those 
days. And he lived on - the - beef and - hard dry biscuits you see and the cocoa The cocoa was hard, with lumps of fat in it. And to make it ordinary you had to - plane it up or - grind it up. And it was full of fat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How long was he in the Navy after you came here to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 He - he came out - when - when we came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} he came out of the Navy. As he - yes, as he took on - yes, he took up his new position you see so he came out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 So from the age of five you don't remember him going away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no, he was in the dock - dockyard, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was he away much when you were very small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I never saw him 'til I was four. He was out on a - four year cruise to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Australia{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}New Zealand{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. So I never saw him 'til I was four and I hated him. D
idn't want that thing coming in - between mother and I. We lived in Portsmouth then you see. And to see this man walking about the house - no, that didn't please me at all. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Can you actually remember this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, I can - no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or have you been told about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, my dear, I can honestly remember it. My mother's brother was my - God. Uncle. And that was the only man I knew to come in the house you see, 'til I was four. Then came this other creature. In his blue uniform. And I think he
 frightened me one day, he frightened me because he - he - brought his box of - great big - big as that table, great big box of tools, he took out a hatchet and chased me, like he might for fun you see and of course - frightened me. I hated him. I never r
e
ally and truly - had the admiration or the love for my father that many children do. Because he came into my life the wrong way you see. And I resented it. Yes. Yes. Mm. He did. I suppose he did - all he could for me and - I was given as good an education
 as they could get here for me. But no, I - I never - felt the - freedom. You see, I was four when I knew him first, and I never got that intimacy or freedom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You never really got very close to him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I suppose that first four yea
rs when you were with your mother you were the only child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I was only a child - was only child altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You must have had a very close relationship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. I'm not exaggerating, I wouldn't exaggerate this to you. I can see him now in that
 - house in Portsmouth, chasing me with a hatchet. I remember screaming. And mother coming out and telling him not to be so silly, you know. Leave her alone. But no, I never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you in fact try to drive him out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you behave in any way to try and get him to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, I knew I couldn't do that. Because I'd heard so much about daddy coming home. I knew I couldn't do that, but if mum - mother and father were sitting in the sitting room - I'd go and sit it the othe
r end of the room. Right away from them. It's something I can't explain quite, the - this stranger coming and taking over this position.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did it in fact change your relationship with your mother much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, I don't think it did. Mother didn't like 
children. Then she only had one. And as a little girl, I couldn't understand why I didn't have any brothers or sisters you see. I thought I have - ought to have some brothers and sisters, so I asked grandma about it one day. Well, her said, I don't know w
h
y you haven't got any. You may do one day. And I - grew up - through - not being so close with my father, I grew up to be a little listener. Rather than a partaker of any conversations. And we were home with grandma once and I remember grandma saying to m
o
ther, well - why not give her another child to play with. Have another child. I remember mother turning round and saying, no. Never will I go through that again. And that stuck in my - immature brain. And I remembered that for years. Oh, what was I then, 
four. Yes. But I'm a very good listener. I grew up to be - all through my life then I grew up to be one - in my childhood, one. By myself. I listened. But I wouldn't talk much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother talk much to you though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. But I - and I remember 
- father was very friendly with the Metropolitan Police down at the yard because - they'd only just taken over the dockyard then, the Metropolitan Police. And they used to come to our house, the young Metropolitan Police and their wives, they used to come
 
and have supper and - tea. And I can remember times - there was - people - remarking how quiet and how good I - I'd sit for hours and listen. I didn't miss anything either. If they talked to me I never - had nothing to say. Mother used to get so angry wit
h me too. 'Til I - when I was older I was made to answer you see. I grew out of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you were living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} then, you were with your mother, was there anybody else living in the house with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, we had a house to ourselves. Grandma
 lived across the road but we were in a house on our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this your mother's mother or your father's mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mother's mother. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you see a lot of her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. By the time I was - born 'til the time I was five, I saw a lot of her
. I lived as much with grandma as I did with mother. Well I'd rather go with grandma, rather than my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have your meals there as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. If I had to choose between the two I'd choose grandma.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was your mother working at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. People didn't work in those days. Mother - mothers and father didn't - your mothers rather didn't go out to work. Mother would have scorned the idea of going out to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother ever work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, she was a - dressmaker. But s
he never went - after she married she didn't work outdoors - didn't work out anywhere at all. Did her own things and mine but - she never went out to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she do any more dressmaking for other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. There's some things didn't do, you 
didn't go to work in those days. You got married and you looked after your home and children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And your father had a good job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Father had a good job, was a very good job in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was he ever out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. Never knew the meani
ng of being out of work. Neither did I. No. You see there was - you were either employed in those days or you weren't. If you had a job you stuck to it. I mean the same with teaching. You had a - a job at teaching, well you had to stick it because you cou
l
dn't afford to throw up your job and - be out of work. Money wasn't plentiful then like it is now. And so I mean - that's why mother being here well I stuck it here because - I knew I couldn't - afford to leave here, I couldn't afford to keep two homes go
ing. And you - you did things to keep your job. And it wasn't like the youngsters today, jump out of this one into that one. Well today they don't stay five minutes do they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you see much of your grandmother then after you moved down here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh 
used to go every Christmas and every summer. So I saw quite a bit of her you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she come and stay here at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Only when mother had the measles. Mother had the measles - measles when she was - thirty-five I think I - remember her saying. So of course grandma came to stay with us then. Grandma ran the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you lived here on Portland you said you lived on High Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there just your father and your mother and yourself in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there any lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have the whole house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Father wouldn't have any lodgers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of house was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
A six roomed house. Yes, a six roomed house. It had nothing - of course that was in 1900, it was newly built.
 Father had to wait for it to be finished before they could go in. They couldn't get a house then. They went in lodgings for three months. Excuse me. They got this newly built house in High Street. It had - six rooms. Nothing very modern, no bathroom of c
ourse. And - no gas fires, nothing like that - in those days you had the ranges or open grate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did it have a kitchen and sort of front room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
There was a front room and a middle room, what they call - in those days they called - the front sitting room and the middle room, and a kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And three bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And three bedrooms, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother have anybody in to help look after the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she do everything herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did everything herself, yes. It wasn
't so easy in those days - or nobody did that sort of thing, not the ordinary - level of people did they. No. Not then. Oh yes. Excuse me. But - in the ordinary course you didn't have anyone to do your work. Mother was very able bodied in those days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she do the washing at home or send it out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did it herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it done in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, scullery. Of course she had the old fashioned rubbing board. And a scrubbing brush. And starch - starch was the great thing. My mother was very
 fond of starch, all my clothes were starched, oh didn't they prick too. You had your knickers done with - embroidery you know and - and piece of - strip of embroidery and they was goffered. Goffered ironed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother make any of your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, made them all. Yes. Yes, she was a dressmaker, made all my clothes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she make clothes for herself as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Some she did but we had another dressmaker in the family so that one was - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, so that one did it sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this a sister of hers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Sister-in-law.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were most of your clothes new then or did you have any secondhand clothes?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You say that to my mother. Yes, everything she - I had was made new. I never had anybody else's leave offs. I never remembered wearing anything of anyone else's, not in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she ever cut things down of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. Always new. Yes. And dare I get them dirty either. You went out to play but you mustn't get yourself dirty. Oh no. The old fashioned idea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember any occasion when you did get dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. I remember an occasion when I fell down and smashed me front teeth in. I was playing out in the - there was a yard to this - house - with a - cement path. And I had no one to play with
, used to play with myself, I was never encouraged to have children in to play with, worse luck. And I tripped one day and I fell on this cement path and smashed my front teeth. When I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 About seven or eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you taken to a dentist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I was taken in - yes, I had to be taken to a doctor and - then to a dentist. Have them patched up. They didn't come out, they broke off. So they - in some way they were patched up. I can't - can't remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were these your first teeth or your second teeth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Mm. Second teeth. I can't remember all the details so when I was eighteen the lot had to come out because I started teaching you see, and in those days you had to - present a clean bill of health. You had to have all 
your teeth out if you had any - bad ones or - poor, and so mine had to come out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you have new clothes for any special occasion, or just when you needed something?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh if you went - when you went home Christmas for - holiday you had a new fro
ck to go home with. A new frock for Christmas. Had a new frock for Easter. And if you went away in the summer you had another new frock. But you didn't have none of this stuff as this - none of the thin stuff. Not - how shall I say, you didn't run about h
a
lf naked like you do now. The kids - they had new frocks, but they weren't - the thin shadowy stuff you use today, no nylon, nothing like that you see, nylons. And - I was rather delicate as a child and I was never allowed in the sea. Because they put me 
i
n the water two or three times and I went blue, so - doctor said no more so - I wasn't bathing or - and that was that. Oh yes, I - I had plenty of clothes, I wasn't kept short of clothes. And mother rather dressed me for her own pleasure you know. I don't
 know if there'd been more of us if we should have been quite so lucky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Where did your mother get the material from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. They used to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 shopping. She'd go to Bennets a lot in those days, Bennets was a much better shop then than it is now. It was a real good class shop. Of course it's Debenhams now. But - oh yes, go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and buy all you wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother make clothes for anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 For any other members of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. There wer
e - other dressmakers in the family you see. There was two more in - near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Cousins and - aunts. Oh she only made for herself. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she make anything for your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no. Yes, separate trade again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about shoes, did you have new shoes, regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, I had plenty of shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Were they just when you needed them or did you have those for special occasions as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well I think I had those, if - if I remember rightly I think shoes came more when they were n
eeded. You took them over to old - Snobby thingmebob over in High Street in those days even, and have them repaired. Peters. Old Man Peters. You took them over to Old Man Peters to be repaired, but if you wanted a new pair you had a new pair.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they bought locally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, there was a - very decent shoe shop here in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, in Queen's Road, when I was a child. Called Stones and they really did - have some very good class stuff. Now it's a - it's a general shop now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother make coats and things like that for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Yes. Everything, yes, she could do - the full range, she could do coats or - frocks or whatever she - whatever you wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember having any bought clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 To tell you the truth, no I can't.
 I don't remember. Until I was - quite a big girl then. Until I was fifteen or sixteen say, or over. No, I don't remember going to the shop and buying - all made for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you allowed to sort of choose patterns and materials?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh I could choos
e materials, yes, which one I liked, this or that. Take me to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to choose it, yes. And you went by train. Went down to - to the station, caught the train in. And you went in for ninepence return. No. That's not right. I believe it was sixpence retur
n. Yes, I think I - sixpence. Ninepence on the busses when they first started. And the man who built it - built it for six twenty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father buy the house that you had in High Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. He - no, he wouldn't buy any houses, he - he a
lways said - that he would like to move back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} if it was possible. But it didn't become possible. So he wouldn't buy a house here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs around the house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, he was a carpenter and he 
amused himself - doing carpentry and he had his own little workshop. He spent his time carpeting, but I don't remember him doing much for mother. Except that - Sundays - father always cooked the Sunday breakfast. That's about all I remember father doing. 
He wasn't a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother stay in bed then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, that was hers and mine. When we came down the breakfast was ready, but he wasn't a man to - take household - duties for her. The old idea that - woman's place was in the home and she did the jo
b, that sort of thing you see. 'Cos that was the old idea wasn't it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he ever help with any of the cleaning then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Not to my knowledge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or the washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh - yes, yes. No, father - yes, no, father didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about the fires in the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I don't remember - I don't remember him lighting a fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother get up and do that first thing in the morning then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Of course in those days he went to work at six o'clock you see so she was up early. She had to be up early. I don't remember father lighting a fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he do the decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 As he rented the house did he do anything in the way of repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh he might do a casual repair - anything that was really - was essential, but I don't remember him - taking that much interest in the place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 He didn't build any cupboards or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No he built - no. No. That wasn't my father at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You say he had his workshop, what sort of things did he do in his workshop?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well this - all this sort of thing. Yes. Making furniture. He made furniture galore. I've sold some of the stuff - when - mother - just - just after mother died I sold quite a lot of it, hand made furniture. He was always making furniture of so
me kind or other. Go home to Portsmouth - on a Christmas and go down the - main - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11276250\charrsid7023924 Commercial}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924  Road and - all those big - shops, look at the furniture that was in the window, come ba}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11276250\charrsid7023924 c}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 k and make it. See? Take his ideas, and come home and make it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he in fact sell any of the furniture that he made then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, he'd give it, he'd give it to my - relations or his - brothers and sisters and that but - no, no, he didn't well it. Didn't make a living out of it, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he do very much for you after 
this period when you got more used to having him around, did he read you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or play games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. No. We never got that close. Mother would play games with me. Ludo and all the other kids games and - read me stories and 
so on, but I learnt to read when I was six, I could read when I was six. She taught me to read. And then I was a real bookworm. With me own little books you see. But - no, father never - never remember father reading to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you ever remember him taking you out on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. I remember, he worked at the dockyard, of course he used to come home to dinner, and I remember - being allowed to walk back part way to the dockyard with him. And then come back by myself. We always - as a - well I supp
ose as a family you see, if father was going out - to take us anywhere, we all - we were all taken, I was taken as well as mother. They didn't go away and - go anywhere without me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have long chats with him while you walked back to the dockyard?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No. We never got that close.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to help carry out any jobs in the home as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. I was made to wash up, I had to do some of the washing up, and my mother took darned good care that I learnt how to do things. Partl
y cooking, but not a lot of cooking. 'Cos I had to do - some cleaning at times and - I had to do it properly. No half doing it. No skipping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would she come and inspect it when you'd done it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, she - yes, and it wasn't done - it had to be done
 again. You know, you laugh about it now but I didn't used to laugh, I used to hate it. And I was allowed out l- to go and play and - played with me playmates. I had quite a few playmates in the High Street in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would you have to do your jobs before you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. And always my music practice, I learnt the piano. I had to do my practice before I could go outside the door. You can go out for half an hour when you've done your practice. Not before.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there any jobs you alw
ays had to do sort of regularly every week or every day? Did you always have to do the washing up every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no. No. Now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 OR WOULD it be your mother would say do something particular on one day?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. I don't remember doing that either. 'Cos I - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Just sometimes then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes - yes, you had to do so and so or she was very busy - do so and so then she'd come and see that I was doing it right. I was a rebellious little devil. I didn't care whether I was doing it right or w
rong so long as I got through it. I look back on it now you know but - used to hate it - and that practice had to be done, although I did get on very well, I got - got to LR - LRAM, but that practice - oh - it had to be done. Do your practice. And Sunday 
mornings - my father was home Sunday mornings of course, so I had to do my practice Sunday mornings so as he could hear - whether I was improving or whether I wasn't. But I did make a fair success of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was your teacher here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. She's dead now. Dead years and years ago. Then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How old were you when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I should think about six. V should think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it one evening, one afternoon a week, something like this, after school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Two lessons a week if I remember right. 
Yes. Mother took good care I did my practice. No getting out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would this be lessons of an hour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Half an hour lesson. Yes. About half an hour - about half an hour's lesson. And then - there had to be an hour's practice every day. Yes, I had
 to get an hour in. I couldn't go out to play 'til I got that hour in. Then there's - there was people in - there was children in the road that I knew see and - we played games - skipping rope. Of course our - games in those days weren't so - numerous as 
they are today. You had your skipping rope and you loved your skipping rope and you had your hoop, and you played \{BLANK\} and you played hide and seek. Don't think you played much else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Your mother didn't mind you going out to play with the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh no, she knew who I was with you see. There was the - some children in the road and - they were approved of so I was allowed to play with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you have limits that you could only go so far? Or certain children that you could just play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well - she didn't limit me - to - with whom I spoke or played, but I was limited to not to go far. I must stay on the street. She must be able to look out of the window and see I was somewhere among the - I wasn't allowed to go off on my own
. And now the children don't ask can they go, they go. Yes, well I mean, take gener - take them generally, the children today, the older children don't ask mother if they can go. They tell her they're going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you always have to tell your mother the
n, right the way through exactly where you were going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Never allowed to go anywhere unless mother knew where I was going.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Even when you were fourteen or so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. My time, when I was fourteen most of my time was spent - practicing. 
But I liked it, although I - disliked it - when I was younger, when I got older and got - really to like music, I liked the practicing. And I was going in for the various exams you see, so they kept you going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 At what age did you start taking music exams?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh now you've asked me something. Subjects you see. I didn't take only one subject but you - you took your class and you kept that one class, and you took it for everything. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What age were they that you started with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh you could - I started with - I think started with elevens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What age did the Cliff school take them at that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
From one - from - five to fourteen. Fourteen, yes, a real - county council school you see. And you had your infants class - infants rooms in
 that school, so it took the five years olds, and you had every other class. I had the - I think I started with elevens. But I went all over the place. I had - elevens and I went down to eights and then I came back somewhere else and I went down to ones, 
s
o I had experience with them all you see. But it was interesting because you'd - had - you know - leave your books to be marked for tomorrow. What writing's done, what exercises were learnt today, if that headmasters knew that you left those books to tomo
rrow they would help you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What work you set one day had to be corrected?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Had to be done, yes, had to be corrected. And he'd come in in - at the end of the week and he'd ask to see the corrections. What corrections you'd make see, and he asked to see where they were now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And you were eighteen when you started there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 That was your first teaching job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. And you didn't - put - you - you made the children write, you made them write, they had to write. They had to write - 
copperplate. I hadn't been teaching many months - when an inspector who was rather feared in those days - came, and he - we had a - what I call a swinging blackboard, a blackboard that used to swing over. He told me he wanted to see me do a copperplate - 
f
or the children. I did it. Put him up his copperplate. I used to like doing that. And - oh yes. That'll do very nicely, you'll do. That's all the commendation I got. Yes. I was all right. I always remember I was taking a - taking a dictation lesson once, 
I
 hadn't been at it very long. Of course dictation's a thing gone now, nobody's - nobody knows what dictation is. They had their exert - you know what it is I suppose. And I was calling out this - dictation you see, and instead of standing still in front o
f
 the class I walked down the aisles, 'cos the desks were - two and - two desks fixed together you see, and then there was a space. And you could walk down the aisle. So instead of standing like a - a mummy, in front of them you see, I walked down the aisl
es, I copped it. What did I mean by walking about like that? Why didn't I stand still in front of the class? So that everybody could see me and hear me. Got a bad mark for that. Oh dear. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And you stayed at the Cliff school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I stayed ther
e - well you see mother was such an invalid I couldn't go away and leave her so I just stayed there. Well then of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How old were you then when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Father died when I was about - fifteen, sixteen. Well then - I entered - I was going to join a house training centre then you see. Well then I went out to this school when I was eighteen. What did you ask me?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You were saying your mother wasn't very well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, she was an invalid you see. And I knew I couldn't go away and 
leave or - or you didn't do it in those days. Children didn't - leave their parents to somebody else to look after. She had no one here you see, no relatives here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When did she become an invalid then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh - what shall I say - in my thirties I sup
pose. Mm. Still only thirty I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 She was still quite fit then when you actually started teaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You were still living at a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 With just your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. And - there was - you couldn't get lodgings h
ere at that time, very difficult to get lodgings, and - we had several teachers living with us at one time. You see, you - you just couldn't get the places. But - I took all classes and then - when they dis - when the county council decided that - this wa
s
n't any longer to be a - senior school, it was to be a junior, and because I'd been taking seniors for so many years then, I was dumped off onto the top. To what is now the secondary modern school. Well then - I so disliked it up there - we had a - a litt
le strut for a headmaster, he came from - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Oh - he'd been in the Army. And he'd got a certain position you see. He was a little strut. I'd never taught history, not all the years I'd been teaching. So he said, you'll become a history mistress. But
 I said, my dear man I've never taught history. I don't care about that, he said, you - you'll teach history. I thought, right. Have an end to this. 'Cos mother was dead then. And - what else did he tell me to do? Came into the room one day he said, and -
 
where's all your pictures? Where's all the information you should have on the walls? Well I said, I hope it's in their heads, not on the walls. I want to see these walls covered with pictures, he said, and information. Now just about that time the county 
s
ent out - enquiries for - people to volunteer to take up teaching of handic - mentally handicapped children. So I thought, now here's a chance to get away from that old devil. So I put in my name you see and I got sent to London for training, and I got se
nt to - Bridport, and - oh one or two places they send you for training, so I got away from that old devil by - I was glad to get away from him. But I liked teaching the handicapped children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You came back and taught them here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I came - yes, the
re was a special class - there was a special class formed up there for mentally handicapped children because we had - quite a - quite a few of them. But I liked it. I liked the training and I liked the work. If you can get round the right side of those ch
ildren you know they'll do anything for you. And they improve. I - I must show you a piece of work one day they done down here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I think you told me about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh did I, yes. Yes. That's right. I was afraid - I've got the piece now. She - went ahead like wildlife. Got into an A section. Just because she was interested in - somebody took interest in her you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Can we go back to where we were before we were interrupted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Go on then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you were a child, you mentioned that your 
mother gave you these odd jobs to do occasionally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to do more as you got older to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No because I was kept - more at the music. You see, she kept me in the music. Well she and father between 'em, and I was 
taught to - do crochet and taught to make things in knitting and crochet. So I wasn't given housework to do. Consequently I never became very fond of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Your mother taught you to do crochet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh when I was five, yes. When I was five I was croche
ting antimacassars. I don't how my little fingers went round that crochet hook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she sit and supervise you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes. See that I did it properly. And I learnt it, I - yes, I could - I could crochet. I can now. Although of course it's more difficult for me to do now because my hand - I haven't got the - the full control of that hand, I }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11276250\charrsid7023924 have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
 in most cases, I can write yes as you saw, up to a style, but I can knit better than I can crochet. 'Cos of course when you have the crochet in your hand - you've got to put it in here - to a small space.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother make you go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. When I was small. Well - I was allowed to stay up 'til nine - when I was about - from the time I was about nine I suppose. Go to bed at nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this during schooldays and holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Always. In bed at nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she have a special routine then, in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well amuse myself - or practice or amuse myself for a while and then when nine o'clock came - off to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How old were you when you first put yourself to bed, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Mm, no, I - I suppose that came - you see father was so very ill - before he died and I was - I had to look after myself quite a lot because - he was desperately ill. Before he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What did he die of then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
He was going - went in the dockyard one morning, it was Christmas. And we were going home that day to Christmas - to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 for the Christmas, and he caught his - two of his fingers in the sawmil
l. And he came out of the dockyard with them hanging off, and he wouldn't go into hospital and he wouldn't go and have them seen to, and septic poisoning set in. It affected the brain. And he didn't go mad, but he went - very near to it. And then - oh wha
t was that other disease set in? Hm. I can't say the name of the disease I want.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it a form of gangrene?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, that was in the fingers, but - something set in in his back, in the backbone. From the poison on the fingers. Doctor Howard was very 
good to him and did what he could but of course - like he said, they should - he shouldn't have - gone off and not had them - anyway he had to have both fingers taken off. And - he was never the same after he had to give up work. There was that see, so of
 course - I was left more on my own. To - you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to do a lot in the house at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, never - never heavy work. Mother never gave me heavy work to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she have a lot of nursing to do then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, and he was very very ill. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to help with the nursing side of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Not that I remember. No. I was considered too young to see - allowed to know anything, in those days you was kept children in the dark more than you - allow them to know anything didn't you. But - I had to amuse myself more from then on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember your reaction when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you upset?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. It sounds awful doesn't it? You see - if only I could make you understand the - repulsion I f
elt - for him because he came into my home. And - we never - grew together. But when he died it didn't make that amount - didn't make the affect on me. Oh I suppose it made a certain affect on me. But - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was your mother very upset?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. Of
 course. It was her livelihood gone you see. And she had to turn to and - we - we kept a boarding house for a short while. Down in Fortuneswell. But no, it never affected me very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You had to move then after your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well we did, ye
s. We moved to a bigger house you see, 'cos she was going to - do this boarding and letting. And of course the house was too small in High Street so we moved right down in Fortuneswell. Do you know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11276250\charrsid7023924 where}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924  the - do you know where the turf shop is down in For
tuneswell? No. No. No. Doesn't matter. Yes. Well you haven't been here that long have you to know, and if you're not down there a lot you wouldn't know, I mean I lived down there so I know it quite well. Oh we had a boarding house for - several -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You were still living at home at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you in fact go away from home at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, I had no chance. My mother took darned good care I didn't go anywhere. 'Cos she - she was rather too possessive. She was a - what I would call a possessive nature. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You were saying that you put yourself to bed. You had your own bedroom?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Always had your own bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When I was little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You said you didn't have a bathroom at the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Not in High Street, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have a bath brought in in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
In the - in the kitchen, yes, in the kit - in the scullery. You couldn't have a - there was no bathrooms then you see and there was no compulsion about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have a regular night of the week do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well I - I can't remember. I know I was made to bath every week but I really couldn't tell you - no, I don't think we had any - Friday night must be bath night, don't think we had any of that. Yes. Yes. Well I was given clean 
clothes every - weekend, I remember that, but I can't tell you whether it was Saturday or Sunday, didn't matter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have your meals in the kitchen or in the middle room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, we kept the - mother had a gas stove in the scullery, and that mea
nt if you came into the middle room it was rather a long way to walk with everything. So we had our meals in the kitchen usually. It was - furnished quite nicely I remember - matter of fact it wasn't furnished like a kitchen at all. More like - more like 
a little living room you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you use the other rooms all the time then or were they kept just for guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh the middle room we weren't - we didn't use very often. But the front room was used a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would they use it in the evening to sit in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Sometimes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 That was where the piano was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 That's right where the piano was, yes. Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there any occasions when you would eat in the other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh if we had - visitors or - we used to have quite a few visitor
s in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You mentioned your mother had a gas stove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I think she was - one of the first to have one in a new house in those place. Because of course she'd been used to it in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And when she came here there was none. So father had the gas put in almost immediately he got into this house. That was the day we had the electricity in first. Because it hasn't been so many years here you see. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have paraffin lamps then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I do remember taking candles to bed quite pla
inly. And paraffin lamps we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How old were you when the electricity was put in then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I can't remember my dear. Oh I was quite grown up. We were living down Osborne Terrace. I can't remember. Matter of fact the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was that where the boarding house was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, that's where we had the boarding house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You mentioned your father had to be in work and got up very early at six o'clock. Your mother got up at the same time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Got up to see him off, yes. Cooked his breakfast and sent him off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she have her breakfast then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I couldn't tell you what -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or did she have breakfast with you later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I can remember her bringing breakfast up to me. As a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 She used to bring it regularly upstairs to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Ye
s I think she did. As a matter of fact I hadn't thought about that. So long ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he work Saturday mornings as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Everybody worked 'til midday Saturday in those days. There was no five day week then. Yes, worked a Saturday right up to - dinner time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And Sunday morning your father used to cook the breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, used to cook breakfast. Big institution.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of meal would your father have for breakfast in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well far as - as far as I can remem
ber - when he was home and I was home and we had breakfast together it was bacon and eggs always, but - what he did other mornings I really couldn't tell you because I wasn't there you see. I wasn't up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you normally have a cooked breakfast then every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
To tell you the honest truth I can't remember. I - I honestly can't remember - whether I did or didn't, I don't know. I had something to eat I remember. That was enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 At dinnertime did you come home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. No school dinners in my -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father come home for dinner as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. No, not always. He did so for a few years and then he stayed - he took - lunch, and had a - meal when he came home. We all had a meal when he came home. Oh was no school dinners when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would your mother cook a cooked meal at dinnertime then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Even after your father stayed at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. When father stayed - in the dockyard to dinner, we had a meal - in the evening. Five or six, and we'd have something cold for - we made do with some - something cold or - whatever was going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Would you have tea then, if you had dinner at midday, a cooked meal at dinner time, would you have a sort of a tea or high tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh just ordinary bread and butter a
nd some - no cooked again, no. I don't remember that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And Sunday did you have any special sort of food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 A special big dinner or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, just a cooked dinner. Yes. Nothing - out of the ordinary you know, nothing - elaborate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was Sunday tea any different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No. I don't remember that being any extra.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would you have cake in the week regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Mother was a great cake maker. And - when I was - oh, fairly young, I can't remember how young
 I'd be, twelve or thirteen perhaps - the Paisley Cornflour Company - used to come round and give demonstrations. And they came here to Portland two or three times and mother went there, oh and she brought home some lovely cakes that she made some lovely 
cakes after that you see, went to these cookery classes. But she was a very good cake maker. In fact she was a very good cook altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she like cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, she liked cooking. She was a good cook. Remember the stews she used to make some 
lovely stews. Never - boiled stews, always - in an oven. Put in a large pie dish or - I can see the old pie dish now, great big thing. Bigger than that. And all the - stew was put in the oven and covered over. Which you call a casserole today I suppose. O
h yes, she was a very good cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there always plenty of food then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. We were never short of food. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you allowed to eat other than at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 If I wanted but - it wasn't a general thing. I can remember asking for som
ething to eat. But - it wasn't general.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. Grandma did. Mother didn't, grandma did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Grandma in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, she used to make her own bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, al
ways. Always made apple jam and plum jam. We always had ap - apple jam in the house. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Plum{\*\xmlclose}
 jam, gooseberry jam. Grandma used to make - a kind of jam like I can't remember how it was made, but I remember as a child being very fond of it. Carrot jam. But I ca
n't remember a word about how it was made. But it was very lovely. Because my grandmother was a cook before she was married. Yes, she was - a gentleman's cook. So she knew a bit about cooking. The old days of cooking that would be of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Where would your mother get the fruit from to make the jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Buy it from the shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 She'd go and buy it specially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Go and buy it, yes. Yes. And I mean you - fruit was - very cheap then to what it is now. You wouldn't pay eleven pennies for a pound o
f gooseberries or fifteenpence. If you paid - threepence a pound for gooseberries or fourpence - cheese fourpence a pound. I've been sent out many a time to buy a pound of cheese for fourpence. And - then - there used to be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you get sent to do the shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I used to get sent out quite - a bit when I was a - fairly big girl. When I was - quite small - there was several old farmers used to come - into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, used to come in from Chickor and Abbotsbury and all those country places, with a c
art full of - fruit. Then you didn't buy your - apples by the pound. You bought them by the gallon. The gallon measure, the round measure. But you didn't - you - bought a gallon of apples, or a half a gallon. Didn't buy a pound. And when they did the gall
o
n up for you - they piled them up. They didn't just - have them even across the top, they were piled up on the top. And when your milk girl came round - she came round with a big pail of milk. And you went out to the door and took your pint of milk or qua
rt of milk in a jug, and you expected a drop over. If she didn't give you a drop over you told her about it. And I'll swear there isn't a pint of milk in these bottles these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Where were the apples and things kept, in a special store, were they sto
red anywhere for the winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I don't know. Because we - we bought them by the gallon, or half gallon, yes, and of course as soon you had them they were gone, they were eaten.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother bottle fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Tha
t's some - something she didn't. Other people, I've seen other people but mother never liked it. She never bottled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Lovely pickles. Pickled cauliflower, pickled onions, although I never liked pickled onions. Pickled ca
uliflower, pickled gherkins she used to make - do a lot of pickled gherkins in those days. Piccalilli. All those sort of things. She'd have a cupboard full. It wasn't just one bottle, it was a row of bottles you know, in the cupboard. And never believed i
n
 buying a quarter of a pound of tea this week and a quarter pound next week. You bought your tea regularly so that you always had a stock. Mother always had her cupboard stocked, even when she was so ill. You bought the same things this week as you bought
 
last week so that you were never out. So that when the war - when the first world war started - we had quite a lot of tea in the house. We weren't short you see, we - we built up - mother always bought the same amount every week, and built up a good stock
, and - she had a good stock of soap in the house. She didn't believe in just running round the corner and buying a pennorth of this and a pennorth of that. Always kept her cupboard well stocked. That was the old idea again you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she ever make any wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well, she did but not until - toward the end of her life. And then we had what we - what she called bee wine. You bought these - you bought these - bees as they called them, they were - like pieces of white - what can I describe them as
 - you know what a piece of - mm oh not macaroni - what's the other cereal for making - tapioca. You know what a piece of tapioca looks like don't you? Well, it was like lumps of tapioca but they were soft and white, and they worked up and down in a liqui
d
. And you made this - you'd leave these things - bees they were called, you put them in cold water and made them to work and they would - produce a wine. Bee wine it was called, we did that for several years but - you could make yourself drunk on it if yo
u weren't careful. But then after that she - made a lot of - oh - not potato, we didn't like potato wine, turnip wine. Blackberry wine. What are those little yellow flowers called? Not buttercups.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Cowslip?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. Yes, you could make cowslip wine. Th
at took a lot of time because you could only have the little - little golden bits out of them, no, what's the other yellow flower that grows in the hedges? Oh you feed the tortoise on them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Dandelion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Dandelion. Used to make lovely dandelion wi
ne. It's a love - it is a lovely wine when it's made properly. Go out on the Weymouth Road and pick all these dandelions. Come home -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You say she didn't make this until you were much older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh I was - grown up, yes. And - put them in a big bath 
of water. Put in some yeast, and then the toast, and let it work for so many - days or weeks. And then strain it all off. Bottle it. But you mustn't cork it. Yes, we did - she did a lot of that. But I haven't taken any interest in it, not - since I've bee
n - on my own, no. I mean lots of people do now, they make a lot of this - homemade wine don't they. Yes. Some of them, well there's some of them profess to make it but they don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about medicines, did your mother make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or your grandmother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Grandma was very keen on blackcurrant wine. Black - blackcurrant juice, and - blackcurrant jam - with hot water poured on it, if you'd got a cold. That was a - oh yes, that was a wonderful - but nothing more than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father make any beer at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Not in those days. I don't say he didn't drink beer but he never made any. But then people didn't in those days you see. It's only the last - twenty years that that sort of thing has come to the fore hasn't it
. No. No, father - yes, father didn't do anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother or father grow any of their own vegetables, or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Father was a good gardener. He used to plant the seed - and then for a couple of days he couldn't see it coming up
, he'd dig it up and see if it was growing. Oh he was no gardener. No, father was no gardener. But he was a lover of birds. He kept - lovely - mm -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What are Buff Orpington's then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Buff Orpingtons are fowl - a specie of fowl. And - on the yellow
 tint - more of that colour. Their feathers are more that colour. But they're very fine table birds. Oh kept - a lot of the Buff Orpingtons for years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he keep them just for your own table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mostly for our own table. There was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And also for the eggs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
And they lovely egg - the lovely brown eggs they produce. Oh nothing for mother to give somebody a dozen eggs for - get rid of them, she couldn't - use them all you see. She'd give some -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Where did he keep these then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well at
 the - in High Street we had a long yard. And they were kept in - there was - special cages made for them, long - roosts against the wall. OH he kept - and he looked after them well. And - well - nothing to have a - for us - for us was nothing to have a c
h
icken. In those days of course that wasn't a - a general thing. Then of course some would be sent home to grandma sometimes, and some given to somebody and - but - they do produce very lovely eggs, and they're very good table birds. We had a few White Orp
i
ngtons. But only a few. Oh I used to be very fond of those birds. Well they were - company to me you see, 'cos I had no children to play with so - tome as a child they were - companions. 'Cos we didn't have any cats or dogs. Poor old boy - we had one litt
l
e bird I remember - we used to hatch all our own, father had a special - oh - incubator. He had a special incubator, he used to hatch out all his own chickens. And we had one freak. Instead of it coming out a - yellow Buff Orpington, it came out a little 
grey bird. Funny little grey one, little wee thing. And that was my pet for years, this little grey bird. Oh yes, we had - oh - breed all our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you help your father with those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Helped mother with that. Father and mother. I - used to t
hink a lot of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother do things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh she did - she used to look after - look after the birds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of things would she do to look after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well, she'd see that the eggs were kept warm, the - the - little oil lamp in t
his - what do you call it - incubator - it was a big round thing, and you put the eggs round in a circle, and there was a lamp in the centre, fed with oil, you had to keep that lamp burning of course, it mustn't go out or the eggs would get cold. My mothe
r used to - look after these eggs and the - lamp and see that it was burning all the time and - and when the chicks were hatched out she'd - see that they were fed and - little tiny fluffy things. Oh yes, we -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you get given regular jobs to do for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, I - just help - helped out generally. It's a funny thing, although I could pick up those chickens, I could do anything for a chicken, I can't pick up a bird if you paid me now. And haven't been able to for years and years. The very thought 
of picking up a bird - as I feel over cats. They're too - oily, too slimey. Although I love - I'm very fond of nature. But I can't pick up a bird. I had a friend once - used to come here and - if a cat came into this room she'd faint. Yes, she would, she'
d go off in a faint. Go nowhere where there was a cat. And if - she didn't see it - she seemed to have a - a knowledge, she said, where's the cat? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 We didn't cover behaviour at mealtimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh we had - well the old rule you see, you sat - you s
at quiet. I was in the age when - children weren't allowed to talk at mealtimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 If you were spoken to could you answer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Oh yes. But not unless - you didn't start a conversation. You didn't grab.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Could you ask to have things passed to you if you wanted something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh you - yes, you could ask for more but - you didn't talk. I was known as the silent one, because I never talked. My father was - very strict and so was mother. And so you sat still and you ate your food, it was very good food. But you didn't talk.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Could you choose what you wanted to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You had to have what was put down for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you given something of everything and then you had to eat it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or could you say, please mummy, I don't want something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I used to say I didn't like so and so, well I could eat it or leave it. Please myself about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You could leave things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, you could leave it if it you didn't want it, but - you see, I happened to come in that - just
 the end of that era - when - children were seen - and not heard. I just came in - for the last few years of that one. You were seen - I remember my mother and father having company - and people saying - how quiet and well behaved I was. Yes, I sat there 
- I listened to all that was going on but they didn't know what I was thinking. I could have me own thoughts. And sum them up, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Could you ask for second helpings of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, if you wanted it. Or if you were offered it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to hold your knife and your fork in a particular way
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Properly. Oh properly. You had to hold them properly. That's why I can't understand people today, on the television you see children ramming the stuff in their mouth. Great big spoons, ramming it in. Oh no, I was made to - sit at the table properly.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to sit up straight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And sit up straight. No lolling about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you allowed to take a book to the table or anything like that ever?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you were told. Or you could asks to get down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to wait until everybody had finished then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, if you were - if there was several people at the table. You used to wait 'til they'd finished. And you were either told you could go - or you asked to get down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have grace at the beginning of the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Not in our house, father wasn't a religious person. But - oh I had plenty to eat, there was no scarcity of food. But you just - you just had what was given you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have meat then every day of the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Mostly, yes. That or fish. Yes. Well there was no - we weren't short of - money and we weren't short of food. There was a plentiful table. But - as I say, I didn't have the freedom tha
t kids have today, get down when they wanted to. Run round with it in their hands. And - it irritates me now to - to see children doing that, or to know that they can do that. I think it is bad training.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have a certain place at the table where you had to sit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh I had my place at the table, father had his, mother had hers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you served first or did you have to wait?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Now that I can't remember. I don't think I was kept waiting, I think I - mm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you had a birthday would it be different from other days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, my mother and father - to be quite honest - mother didn't like children. But I never had a birthday party. I didn't know what that was. Mother would give me a present and - I had a special tea but I had no party
. But of course I didn't miss it because I never knew what it was you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you ever remember being invited to other childrens birthday parties?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Thought it was funny that they had parties and I didn't. But - mother put it down when I - ta
ckled mother about it in my childish way, she said father didn't like a lot of children round. Which I think was quite true. He didn't, he - he wasn't a lover of children. Of course he'd been abroad so much - on these long - commissions you see, that chil
dren didn't come into his life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of special tea would you have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would you have a cake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And candles on it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no, we didn't have candles on 'cos I think that mother used to make - mo
ther was a very good cook. Used to make me a cake and - we'd have cream on fruit or something like that and - being - you see mother and father were both Devon. So cream was part of our life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about at Christmas time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh of course Chris
tmas - until I was quite a big girl - wasn't spent here at all. As soon as father had finished his duty in the dockyard you see we packed off to Portsmouth. So my Christmas was at Portsmouth with all mother's relations. So I had quite a good Christmas. Mo
ther's - mother's mother, mother's brother, the two children - aunties, cousins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they all living round that area then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 All living round that Portsmouth area see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would you go and stay with your grandmother then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, and we had
 - quite a nice time there. I used to look forward to that, that was my great treat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would you have other children to play with there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would your father spend much time with you at Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No more than ordinary. No more than ordinary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of special things happened at Christmas time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh you went to - this one's house, you went to this auntie first and you went to that auntie\rquote s house. You went to this cousin's house, and they all came back and - general family - intertwining then if you like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 This would be for three or four days, or did your father have more than that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh about - a week we were away. Usually about a week. Oh I used to love that - and traveling by train, I was passionately fond of 
train travel. I would be now if I could do it. Used to look out of the window and see all these people on the railway stations, of course there was crowds there you see. And you wander about and you watch them. Oh I thought that was - lovely. I was always
 fond of traveling. Travelling by train.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You learnt to play the piano you told me?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did either of your parents play musical instruments at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I think father did when he was in the Navy, wind instruments, but he never played them
 when he got home. Because after his death we found - several wind instruments. But I don't remember him playing. Oh I remember he played a whistle. He was rather good at a whistle. What used to - years ago was called the penny tune. But he'd get some goo
d
 tunes out of that. I remember that. But - oh mother - yes, mother played the piano a little. Not much but just a little. But she took good care her daughter played. And her daughter stuck at it. And her daughter passed the exams. Yes, oh I got a LARM of 
it - LRAM.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would you have said that you were a musical family then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well there's music - the ones that lived in Portsmouth, some of those are musical. But I wouldn't call it a - an extraordinary musical family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were your mother and father particularly interested in music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they listen to it on the radio?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No radio then. Girl, what are you thinking about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or did they have an early gramaphone or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Now - yes. I remember when I was - oh I suppose I must 
have been eight or nine - father bought a gramaphone. I think we were one of the first people in Portland to have one. Oh, wonderful. Wonderful. And all the different records, round records you held on your two fingers, only made of beeswax of course and 
y
ou - daren't touch them. You touched them with your hand they wouldn't play. Oh we had a lot of fun with that one. That was taken home the first Christmas we had it for grandpa to see it. And grandpa thought that was wonderful. 'Cos he was an old man then
 you see. Somewhere about sixty I suppose. Sixty or seventy. He thought that was very wonderful. So did I as a kid then. Think it was wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I hadn't hear you mention your grandfather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh he was a great playmate of mine. When I was home. Yes.
 Yes. Yes. Oh yes, I like Dorchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I was wondering why your parents were so keen on you learning the piano?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well because it's something to have somebody in the family that plays piano isn't it. And I had an ability for that, I could do that. But I knew I was going to be a schoolteacher when I was quite small.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this your decision?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
My decision. My father said no. No. Grandma said no. And father said no. You'll go in the Post Office. So when I was about twelve years old - he told m
e plainly that he wanted me to go in the Post Office. And my nasty little - backhanded brain said no, I'm not going. And I didn't. So when the time came to - sit for the exam, there was - there was one - one vacancy. And Miss Lovell was running the school
 I was attending, the - said, oh you'll be all right. So I sat with another girl. I thought, this is too - went in my mind, I said, this is too damned easy. It was easy to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 This was a special entrance examination for the Post Office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Too easy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you fourteen or sixteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Barely fourteen. Too easy. No, I was fifteen. Very - too easy. So - and I've got to get out of this somehow. I've got to get out of this. I'm not going in that Post Office, and I've got to get out of it. So the las
t sum - on the arith - on the arithmetic papers was a bit of a teaser. It had some rather intricate little measurements. Ah - no - that's one way of getting out of this, do it all wrong. So I did that one all wrong purposely. I never told my mother for ye
ars after, 'cos father died just after. I never told her for years I deliberately did it wrong. So as I wouldn't have to go into the Post Office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Why was he so keen on the Post Office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I don't know. Because it's government I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Had he an
y particular reason to be against you being a schoolteacher, or was it the length of the training?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I don't know if he had any reason, but I think he thought if - you were under government you were safe. See, being under government himself all his lif
e, so when - father died, of course and - this other girl got the - Post Office job, she's dead now, she got the Post Office job so I told mother I'd - I'd be a nurse. I - mother didn't want me to be a schoolteacher. I'd be a nurse. Oh no you wouldn't. Yo
u
r father wouldn't allow you to scrub - of course in those days you see - young nurses had to scrub wards, the work was hard. And I wasn't particularly strong. So mother put a bar on that. Well in a small place like this going back all those years, there w
a
s only one thing else to do and that was to - go in for teaching. There was nothing else - going - counter job if you lie. But I - I wasn't going behind a shop counter, I'd - quite made my mind for that. So the only thing to do was to be a teacher. And a 
t
eacher I became. And did forty-five years of it. Yes. But of course the schools changed a lot in those years. I mean you did away - gradually the long heavy desks were done away with. And - they became a little more slack than they were when I was a kid. 
I was taught - copperplate writing when I was a child. As part of my training, you had to do copperplate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You started school here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Which school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What is now known as Brackenbury.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 The one up here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 So this was the local school board?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
That was the local school, it wasn't a council school. It was owned by the chapel. By the Brackenbury people, yes. Methodist, that's right. There was - one other -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Six when I went to sc
hool. Yes, 'cos I - I wasn't very strong as a - little - kid, I was - sickly. But I could read when I went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Whose decision was it that you didn't start school at five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Doctor I think, yes, mother was told not to send me to school too s
oon. I'd had scarlet fever, I had had - something wrong in me neck and so my - head drooped over on my shoulder for - over twelve months. Had a big Abscess that side, big abscess in my neck. And it caused my head to fall. Well I used to be - I was a delic
ate child, and he recommended I didn't go until I was six. So I went to school when I was six. And I could read by that time, mother taught me to read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother do sort of lessons with you then in that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well yes, just all - bits of - 
and taught me to add up and - that's about all you did in school in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You told me she taught you needlework.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Taught me crochet and needlework. And the - the needlework in schools in those days was - long seams of pillowcases a
nd - chemises and things like that you know. And if they weren't very very fine stitches well you took it out again. And you made it all dirty. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you sort of do it in a structured manner, sort of spend so long in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh eveni
ngs mostly. But - when you got to school of course you had a - a teacher for needlework. A special teacher for needlework I remember I had. And you had to do these long seams on pillowcases. Oh I hated them. And you'd to make little fine stitches you know
, little tiny fine needles. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you find that starting school - that year later that this was difficult getting to know the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have any problems mixing with the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No. No. Not really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you like school then when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh up to a point. Yes. Yes, I enjoyed it. 'Cos I could do as I liked. See where - whereas my homelife was a little bit restricted, when you got to school you could talk to who you liked. Or to whom 
you liked I should say. Could talk to whom you liked and - if you wanted to be cheeky to them you could be cheeky couldn't you. There was no one to tell you to be quiet and behave yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You mean to the to her children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Oh you wouldn't d
o it to teachers in class. Not in those days. No, I got on all right in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How long did you stay at Brackenbury then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I stayed at Brackenbury 'til I was about twelve years old. And then I went to this - centre, this big private school. And I found it very hard.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 That was Miss Dartmouth's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Miss - Love. She was Miss Love. She kept a school and she called it Dartmouth House school. But they were excellent - women, there were three sisters, and very - well educated women and they were excellent mistresses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 This school was down near the - near where the park is now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 On - no, Ventnor Road - when I went to it. In Ventnor Road, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 On one of those houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 One of those big houses at the far end, this end, where t
hey're bigger. The houses this end of Ventnor Road are larger than the ones at the other end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 So it's one of the houses that are still there now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. But not a school now, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 About how many children were there there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh - 
we older ones were on the top floor. And there's twenty or thirty of us. And then there was the - juniors. They were on the second floor. I suppose about as many, oh about forty of us altogether. But they - the - the two - the sisters were - very - good. 
Y
ou didn't get out of anything, you know, you were made to learn. And you bought home a nice lot of homework every night to do. Piles of it. They took me through the Oxford exam. I found - at first I found it difficult, yes, I found it difficult at first b
ecause - in the - Brackenbury school you see you - just had the teachers talking to you and telling you the old fashioned style. And when I came to do self study, I found it a bit hard at first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You mean at Brackenbury you were given set work to do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well at Brackenbury you had a teacher standing up in front of the class like you did in all the old schools. And they taught you - what they knew. Whether it was correct or incorrect. They taught you what they knew, you didn't have any - actual st
udy to do. You had your writing lessons and you had your - geography lesson and you had your - from a great big map stuck up in front of you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 But you sort of listened and copied?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You listened, yes. You didn't have to study it yourself. Well when
 I went to this school - we had special books we had to buy of course, special - geography books, history books - all concentrated - knowledge, and you had to learn it. You didn't just read it, you learnt it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to sort of work on your own and find things out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Yes. Mm. You didn't have them told to you at all, you had to - work it out, find it out for yourself. Of course muggings found that a bit hard at first. But then afterwards it came - quite easy. I went through - quite easily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Why did you change at the age of twelve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Because mother discovered that I wasn't doing anything at this Methodist school, I wasn't - getting on, I wasn't learning much. And she wasn't satisfied. So they put me to this school so as I should be 
- better informed you see. And then when I - got so interested in it all - I quite decided I was going - to go for the Oxford exam - yes Oxford - and when I had passed that she said I could go in as a - student teacher. Monitor they called them then, didn
't call them student teachers. Oh the excitement of - I rather liked it you know, going in for the exams. All the excitement of - getting it all up. Oh I liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you say you went as monitor, would this be in the Dartmouth school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no, in
 - county school. I went back to Brackenbury. And you two - spent two years, and in that two years you were monitor, you were called a monitor. In that two years you were taught how to teach.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you actually have to take a class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, with a
nother - with your - with a much older teacher, you stayed with her - or him, and you gave orders as they showed you. And you were taught how to mark books properly. Well you were taught - how to teach you see. Whereas today they don't - consequently ther
e's no rule.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Going back to Brackenbury then, when you started at six did you go a full day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Oh yes. No half days in those days. Yes. Oh yes, they - come home to dinner and go back again, come home at four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 As far as I remember I went by myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How did you get on with the teachers then at Brackenbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh all right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they take much notice of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Treated me as one of the others, I - I wasn't made any special fuss of. I don't remember
 ever being made a fuss of by any teacher. I just took me - place with all the rest. But when I went to - Dartmouth House school of course we were made - I mean - we got individual attention.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What size class would you have been in at Brackenbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh thirty or forty. Yes, mixed classes. And they weren't one - there was one big room downstairs, a - great big - schoolroom, and you had three or four classes in that - room you see, with - partitions, wooden partitions between. But you could hear - wha
t that class was doing down there you could hear. And what - you were doing they could hear. Were no sets - no - separate classrooms. You were all in one big room - by screens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What was the behaviour like at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Not bad. The behaviour w
as - all right. You never - I only remember one boy ever crossing the headmaster. And he went out neck and crop. He stood up to the headmaster and he was going to - oh he was going to do wonderful things. He wasn't going to - he - he stood up and thought 
he - threw - threw the inkwell at him I believe. But he didn't come back anymore. Out. Finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would he have gone to the other local council school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, he wouldn't be admitted again. If you were - what's the word - hm - oh - expelled - if you were expelled no other school'd take you. And there was only one other school here, that was the - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St John{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 So there was the Methodist school and the church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. That's the only two under hill and there was only one on top. The
 - Methodist school on the top.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go to the Methodist one because you belonged to the Methodist church?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or because it was the nearest school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
My parents knew the headmaster of that school. I think that's why I was sent there. They knew the headmaster quite well, so I was sent there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What was the discipline like then in Brackenbury?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Quite good. You talked and you got - you got punished. If they found you talking you got punished. If you were impudent or rude, if anybody was - look out, you got caned. And that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 The boys and the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Caned on the hands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Caned on the hands mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they male teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Some male, some female. Mostly female. I remember one - 
two males teachers, but otherwise they were female. And in those days you see you didn't take one subject, you weren't a specialist. I wasn't for years. You took all the subjects. And your scripture came first, you had three quarters of an hour scripture 
f
irst thing in the morning. And then you - went on to arithmetic or whatever - arithmetic mostly. And then you had - what they called drill in those days. And - no games, but you had your playtime. And then you did various lessons you see, history or geogr
aphy or - whatever it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would you be with the same teacher then the whole time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Nearly always, yes. Mm. Yes. But that teacher of course, took all subjects. You didn't take one subject like today, you weren't a specialist you - took them all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did the teachers emphasise such things as manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. You were - if you were rude you were told of it and you were made to - see otherwise. Didn't have any special lessons in manners, but - well I didn't need teaching as my mother and father were so strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they emphasize tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they emphasize tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, up to a certain degree. But then of course in those days there were no school uniforms. So some of the poor little beggars came looking shamef
ul and - some didn't. I was always sent to school looking - a pick and span. But - you had no school uniforms in those days, then of course the salaries of parents, some of the parents were - very poorly paid, so they couldn't give them - very good clothe
s. And there were larger families in those days than there are today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they bothered say about hands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You had to show your hands to the teachers every so often. And a nurse came once in a blue moon to make sure you hadn't go anything in your
 hair. Which was common in those days. And you got sent home. I never remember being sent home, I was never sent home - and then toward the latter part of my time up there - they insist - instituted the doctor coming round once every year to see you. That
's how they found out that my eyes weren't too good. But - I don't remember anything else, only - he came round once - once in twelve months and you were - if you were a certain age you were examined. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they bother about punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
 And - sorry - punctuality had attendance. Because in those days - excuse me - in those days when you were - when I was at Brackenbury - all head teachers were paid according to the attendance of their school. You see, you had to keep your attendance up t
o
 keep your salary up. So you had - special men employed, come to the school and find out who was away, and go round all the houses and gather the children in as quickly as possible. 'Cos you see - they had too many - non-attendances - well your salary wen
t down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there much problem with this at Brackenbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Well it - it's - And you went up in the churchyard, I hear the old man saying now, you went up in the churchyard to get blackberries - to get some jampots. You see, years ago - peop
le used to put these jampots on the grave and put flowers in them. So that we'd been up to get some jampots. And that's a-true one. I can see that boy now, he's living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} somewhere now. I suppose he's still alive. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And that was an actual case of a man who kept the child off school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. That didn't pay the headmaster you see, to have him kept home like that. Had to keep him in school. Another funny piece I remember - we used to get inspectors come round, you know, to the schools to ma
ke sure that everything was going all right. Well there was one used to come to Brackenbury, I can see him - man now. Great big man, huge man. That to little five year olds he must have looked like a man mountain I should think. Well I was with a teacher 
w
ho was taking - scripture, and - at that time this great huge thing came in, I was half afraid of him myself leave alone the kids. He started questioning them about the scripture they'd been doing you see. So all of a sudden he said, now who can tell me w
h
o was Enemus the sorcerer? Five year olds. Who was Enemus the sorcerer? One brave little chap stood up, I can see him now, he was called Frampton, please sir, the man who saucered his tea. Oh dear. Fancy asking a five year old - who was Enemus the sorcere
r.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this when you were a monitor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would this be the inspector then from the county?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
The county, yes. Yes. And he - he came, he didn't - he didn't examine one subject, but he came into your room and he might be going to ask his
tory questions he might ask this he might ask that. But they were dreaded, because very often you see they'd - down on you - and you were supposed to know everything, well how could you know everything. Taking all subjects you see wasn't easy in those day
s
. Oh I disliked taking drawing, that's one thing I - I couldn't do. I couldn't draw. I was never any good at drawing. And that was one subject I dreaded. I always prayed he'd never come into me while I was taking drawing because I couldn't do the drawing,
 I didn't know what the kids were doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 In Brackenbury did they bother about the way the children spoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well yes, you couldn't say yes to your teacher, you said yes miss or yes sir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they bother about the use of the English language tho
ugh, did they correct their English?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well as near as possible, yes, but - I don't remember English ever being so very badly spoken here. It - you didn't get the - you got the Dorset accent but it - and was some - some of the older people you got the 
- real - Taunton language, but not the children much. Not with the children so much, no. And that's dying out now. The dialect is dying down now to what it used to be. Oh yes, yes. Dialect is dying everywhere. I used to love to hear the Devon dialect. It'
s a pretty dialect, a singing - I can never speak it but - my uncle when I used to go home of course he used to call me - Dorset, he said I spoke Dorset. I suppose I do to a certain extent. Yes. Yes, you pick it up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your parents show an interest in what you were doing in school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Especially when I got to - Dartmouth House, of course father was dead then And mother used to take a lot of interest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she ask you when you came home what you had been doing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And if I couldn't do an
ything she'd help me. She helped me quite a lot. 'Cos she wasn't a fool herself, and she used to sit down with me and - help me with my lessons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she bother much while you were up at Brackenbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she go to the school to see your teachers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, she had nothing to go for unless I was ill you see, and I was - went - took me to the doctor like that, no, she never went. Mother never went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there much difference between Brackenbury and St John's do you think?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 In the standards of behaviour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or in the discipline or the type of children that went to one or the other?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, I don't think so. It's only that you went there and - you went here, o
r you went there. Whichever your parents chose but there was very little difference. As far as - in my - younger days, it seemed to me that teachers at St John's were all older people. I don't remember any young people there. They were all older people. I
 can't remember any young teachers there. And the same teachers went on year after year after year. But, no, they all seemed to be on the older type.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Schools sometimes get a reputation for one being a better school than the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, they do
, yes. Yes. No, I don't think there was much difference in them. I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did the teachers single out some of the children for different treatment from the others at all do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh I don't remember being - singled out or remember any being singled out.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 The rougher children or children from poorer homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well sometimes you got - I think they got notes from parents - asking that they shouldn't be put with certain children who were known to be - from very poor or dirty homes you know but - no, there was no singling out that I know of.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did the children sort of split up into gangs or groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. You got that. You got little groups - used - you made friends with certain ones, of their own type you know. You woul
dn't be seen with the - or say - shall we say the crumbier sort, or you wouldn't be seen with certain ones who came from - very bad homes. But there were some very poor homes here. Down in the Chiswell area. Of course a lot of them are gone now. Houses ar
e gone, families are gone. But - apart from that, no, there was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Is there anybody still alive who lived down this area at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What do you mean still alive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Down in Chiswell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 People still alive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Any children that you were at school with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I think - majority of them are dead that I remember. One died last month. One that had - lived - in the Chiswell area. But anyway she was brought up very very poorly but she ended up with her own house and left - several thousands. No,
 I think most of my - schoolmates - are dead. There's one living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}King Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, one man living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}King Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Well he's seventy-nine and I'm seventy-seven so there isn't much difference in us. 'Cos the last time I was up the street he spoke to me. But I don't think there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have any particular friends when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, you had the few you - hobnobbed with, you know, that you played with or played with you and - you sat with or you didn't sit with or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would these children live near to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Not always. Depends - what type of child they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they children from similar sort of backgrounds to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 As - yes, similar background.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of jobs did their father do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well some of them w
ere in the dockyard you see with father, that's how I got to know some of them, and some of them - were - just my own choosing. But of course you didn't play out in the streets 'til - eleven and twelve o'clock at night in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you allowed to go and see these schoolfriends after school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, if - sometimes I was allowed to go out and play with them or go to their homes and play with them for a little while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they all live then actually in this sort of area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh - yes, yes, round, yes, High - High Street and Fortuneswell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother say you'd got to be back at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Yes, certain time. If you weren't there a certain time you didn't go again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have to sort of say exactly where you were going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And stay there? Or were you allowed to go out for walks with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You told - if you went out you had to tell your parents exactly where you were going and with whom you were going. You didn't say mind your own busi
ness or go - I'm not going to tell you. Oh no. You had to say where you were going. So if mother choose to come and fetch you she could see. Oh our life was - for children it was much stricter but I think - the lessening of this strictness has been the do
w
nfall - of discipline. I think that - children are by far better - for discipline, than they are without it. At least I think so. Well there's a - three children out here the other afternoon. I'm sure they were - all under ten. Little mites playing with -
 
bicycles and so on. And the painter that was here, he went out to his car to get some paint and - just spoke to one of them. Now son - what are you doing, or something like that you know. Shut your gob. Oh. If he'd been a child of mine I'd have broken you
r
 neck. So of course he - he turned round and he said don't you talk to me like that, he said, I spoke nicely to you. Go on, get yourself out of it. Well - you know it isn't all - childish - they must hear that sort of thing. No. They were well dressed. Ni
cely dressed children. I think they came from that new - place up here, Par - something Mead. A new - new estate up here. Oh, something Mead. Begins with a P.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Would you ever have got any of this sort of behaviour, even amongst the poorer or the rougher families?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I don't remember - if - bad as - like it in my time. Mind, I was fairly strict. I was known to be strict. But - I don't remember having a lot of cheek from children. I used to get on as children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you think the parents like the one
s you were mentioning down Chiswell were very strict on this sort of behaviour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well I think - no matter whether it's poor or rich there was a certain strictness wasn't there, a certain discipline - amongst the poor as much as the others. It wasn't k
nown for children to be - like they are now. We're living in a different age - there's a different outlook altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
When you changed to Miss Love's school, did your parents then have to pay for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, that was paid, had to be paid for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there many other children that you knew that went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, quite a few.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or did the children come from all over the island?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. No, they came from the island. Yes, oh no, it was all round here. I knew most of them - business
 peoples children - mostly. But they were - quite a lot of them were business peoples children if I remember rightly. People who could - could afford to pay for their child to be educated you see. And of course you - your manners there were very - strictl
y
 seen to, you weren't allowed to be rude, and - I went into school one day - you know what kids are, I ran along Ventnor Road and the wind blew me hat off. So I went into school with in me hand. I must learn to grow up to be a lady. You don't carry your h
at in your hand. You wear it properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this one of the sort of things they emphasised?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Yes. At one time - we wore gloves, we had to wear gloves to school. But that dropped off if I remember rightly. I think that dropped off. Poor old muggings went in without her hat, her hat was in me hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have a full uniform there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, you didn't have to wear uniform. Had no uniform.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 But they said you had to have a hat?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh you wouldn't go to school without a hat. You mu
st go in - with your hat on. You had a place to hang up your hat of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they lay down any other rules about what you had to wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh no, because - you see we were - we all came from homes that were - fairly well supplied, so we were all 
fairly well dressed. You know what I mean, I'm not being snobbish, but - you weren't the poorest of children, and your parents could afford to send you to school - decently dressed. Oh no, we had no uniform but - we were all - we were all quite well dress
ed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Were there extra lessons or extra subjects that you could take if you paid extra?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, there was singing but I never had a voice so that didn't matter did it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have music lessons there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, and I had my music lessons there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they part of the normal curriculum?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. You went for your lessons - special times. Evenings or - during the dinner hour or - before school. You paid extra for that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they teach you some other instruments then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yo
u could take violin lessons or piano lessons, which you liked. I was no good at the violin so - I started once but - mother was told that I was making no progress, I wasn't interested. And I wasn't interested. I am now but I wasn't then. But - I stuck to 
the piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there any other extras like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, I don't remember any more. Singing was extra. You didn't take needlework up there. Music was extra. Violin was extra. No, I don't remember any others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You mentioned that they were very strict about you wearing a hat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
What other things were they strict about, or did they emphasise as being important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well you - had to close the door behind you, you went in a door - you went in a front door at the house you see, and y
ou had to go up all the stairs because - we were on the top floor. And you went up very quietly. If you were heard running up the stairs - you were for it. You went up very quietly. You behaved like a lady.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What other things did they emphasise as being part of being a lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there deportment lessons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, we didn't have deportment. Manners to one another you - you didn't shout, you didn't - use rude words to one another or - and never rude to your teacher of course. You'd di
e if you did. But that's why I think - children have lost the discipline, therefore - they've lost the - sense to care.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did any of the other children transfer to Miss Love's school at the same time as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well there was always somebody coming -
 always one or two leaving and one or two going. But I don't - quite a lot of the Wesleyan children didn't go there of course. And I lost touch with quite a lot of my friends because I went to - what they said the - private school you see. Of course -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there feeling about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. There was a feeling about it in those days. If you went to that school you lost all your old pals from the other school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of things did they say to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well, you were supposed to be - too proud
, and you - you'd gone up one and - you were too good to mix with them and so on, but you didn't have time to go out and mix with them because you were so busy - so busy doing your home lessons, you had piles to get through each night, so you didn't have 
time to go out to mix with your old friends. You had compositions to do. Used to have - pages of it and - you had - geography to do for the next day or history to do for the next day you see. And - heaven help you if you didn't know it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were all children working towards exams?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Most of them were. But there were some there that were only there for the - bit of education or to be away from the others, the poorer children. But the majority of us were all taking exams. Were going into some - part of - 
industry or the other. I knew I was going in for teaching. Some are going in the Post Office and then of course - gradually things opened up as there was other ways of getting a living.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you enjoy school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, I liked it up there. I enjoyed it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How did you get on with the teachers there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Fine. I liked those three sisters very much. They were - well shall we say, of that age - ladies, who had had the better education and were no - earning a living by giving it to others, or as much as they could. Oh yes, I liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they Portlanders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. I forget where they did - they'd been here a number of years, and had been brought up here, because their father was in one of the - now - what do you call those people? Love 
and Company. They were - mixed up with trade, the - stone trade, the coming and going of stone. Sending stone abroad, and sending it to the various centres where it was wanted. That was their - their trade. Well then they were here from children you see. 
Alex Love, the old man - the father was dead, but he - worked this trade up - from nothing almost and made a big - thing of it. There was a lot of money in it in those days of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this the only private school on the island?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How long could you stay at Miss Love's school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You stayed 'til you were sixteen. And they asked you not to go then, you - weren't supposed to stay - after you were sixteen. They didn't like them to keep any - more than sixteen. Well that was really old e
nough in those days you see because - children went to work so much - earlier didn't they. Oh yes, fifteen, yes. Sixteen was the finish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What happened then to most of the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well either they lived a life of - ease, of course, living at ho
me doing nothing, or you went out to whatever you were going to do. Post Office, nursing, teaching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there any of the girls there that went home just to stay at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. Several of them. There was one family especially, I know the three
 sisters from one family, never did a stroke of work after they left school. Simply walked the streets or - helped mother in the house, this was the -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of business was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh one - those three girls came from up - we - we had a very 
big pork butcher here then. Well they came from the pork butchers, and then there were others who had - there was the bakers people, they all - lived at home. You know, didn't go out to work at all, lived at home and lived a life of ease, or worked in the
 shop. Took part in the business. Which I shouldn't have liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I hadn't realized there were people of this sort of level here on Portland.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm. 'hyes. You must remember my dear {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - was a wealthy place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I got the impression that most of the shops were small, small businesses.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well they were small because - well all businesses were small in those days, you didn't have any of these - supermarkets or - all - they were all small businesses. So that they employed their sons and daughters in the business you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I thought you were saying that these girls didn't in fact work in the business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Some of them didn't. Some of them didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 They just stayed at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 They just stayed at home and - well, fooled their time awa
y - my mother used to say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother approve of this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Fooling your time away? Oh no. Get out and work, that's mother's plan. Go out and earn your living. So of course I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What was the name of the pork butchers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Norton. Mm. Mi
nd I'm going back a number of years. He died and of course the business broke up and the family moved away from here. I think the - well I think his wife got married again if I remember rightly, I can't remember properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would these have been sufficiently well established to have servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh some did. Just one.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Come - living in mostly. In those days you see - servants didn't - go out - or come in daily, they usually lived in didn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I hadn't got the impression, 
talking to other people that there were families with servants here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, there weren't many. Very few. They were - quite a lot of people here had money but they didn't - spend it on servants. They spent - they did their own work. There was quite a lo
t of people - mind there are some Bovey families here now you know, especially on Top Hill, people you little think had money. But they made their money in the stone trade you see. But the - Portlanders don't agree in - splashing about. They keep it. An o
l
d man died next door to me here, last April. Well you wouldn't have thought to see him he'd have a penny. He left thousands. And all his life, after his wife - his wife died first - after she was dead they found books in the house - exercise books, everyt
h
ing she brought was - put down. So that she could spend the same amount each week you see. Not overspend. And then they die and leave thousands for somebody else to fool about with. That was a Portland custom. You - you mustn't die and leave nothing. That
 
was a real Portland idea. You must leave something for those - behind you. No matter what you didn't go - what you didn't have yourself - you must leave some money. It was a great disgrace to die and not leave any money. And what I shall leave will be - a
ll a disgrace. I'm not going without anything I want. I can go - only go to a certain limit of course, but I'm not going without - necessities or things I can afford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You haven't got any family to leave it to anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I've got nobody, no. No family. I've got nobody dependent on me you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
If you'd misbehaved at Miss Love's school would you have been punished with the cane there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh no. You'd be shamed. They'd do something to make you feel - very very ashamed. I can't remember - oh yes I
 do, I remember once. We were doing Midsummer Night's Dream. Shakespeares Midsummer Night's Dream, ready for the exam you see. And I was pretty good at learning off by heart. I can now even. Learn by heart. And one line I could not remember which I partic
ularly wanted. So I opened me desk to find it. I found it. But Miss Love found me finding it. So I was made to go to the bottom of the class for the rest of the term.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What did going to the bottom of the class mean then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well sit at the bottom. Ye
s, there was so many desks round the room you see. And if you were exceptionally good at this, that or the other you sat at the top of the class, or if you were the oldest. But if you were down at the bottom you were with somebody who wasn't very brillian
t
. And to sit at the bottom of the class of course was a great disgrace. I never told me mother though. I stayed there all the term. Never told mother. I wanted this particular line and I couldn't remember one particular line. Of Shakespeare's - Midsummer 
Night's Dream. We had to write - a passage on a - prose for - paraphrase a piece and I couldn't remember the line.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it a test then or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, we had tests before the exam you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you not supposed to look up things at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, not supposed to look them up. See, they had the - say they had the papers from the last four years, last four Oxford exams well - they could buy those or send to the Oxford - organisation for them, and use those for coaching. Not that yo
u'd have the same exam - same - questions, you wouldn't, but to use the - get the type of thing you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would these be university entrance papers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I beg your pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were these the university entrance exams?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. They were - for 
outside exams, they were for the university - exams that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I'm trying to establish the level of the exam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well they were pretty stiff some of them, but they weren't university entrance exams.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 If you passed these exams then what could you have gone on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I suppose - I suppose you could have taken another - yes, I think you could have taken another exam to go to the university. You see. You got so far up and then - you would have to go on - learning or being coached to go - into the 
university. I didn't get that far dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You finished at sixteen but people didn't start university even then until much later.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. Eighteen usually wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You mentioned the Weymouth College of Education.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Not me. Oh that was - that's only in recent years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I thought I heard that some went from the grammar school onto there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh I daresay they did. I daresay they have gone from the grammar school to the college, but the college wasn't opened - oh - what's it been going, twenty years? I don't think it's much more than twenty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Was there any entrance into school then, when you started, this system of going to be a monitor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Unless you went to college, and you couldn't - you had to waste two years then, because -
 you couldn't go to college 'til you were eighteen you see. No college would take you 'til you are eighteen. And my mother was left a widow then, and of course she's not left very well off, so I couldn't go. But you - you had to waste two -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was this the university college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, an ordinary training college, yes. Training college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Could they stay at the grammar school 'til they were eighteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Not then. Finished at sixteen then. Oh I don't know. I'm not quite sure about that. No, I think 
they finished at sixteen most of them. Because one or two of them came from - the grammar school to - out here to the Cliff school when I started. And they'd done two years training before they came. There was several of the girls - came out to this schoo
l
, of course I - I came from - Methodist, I came out to this new school on the cliff when I was eighteen you see. And there was several of them came, and they'd done their two years training - up in the Top Methodist school on the Hill. But they'd left the
 grammar school when they were sixteen. Sixteen. Two years, yes, training, yes. Only they'd done it on - on the Hill in the - Methodist school see and I was down here. Well they were all Top Hill girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you'd completed the two years as a monitor d
id you have to take any other exams or any particular tests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, you - no. You took a medical exam. You took a medical exam and applied to the county for - any - vacancy that - occurred you see. Of course you had to get any amount of references, you 
had to get references from the head, references from people who'd known you from - this one and that one. I got mine all right. No trouble.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You told me then your job depended on you keeping discipline.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. If you couldn't keep discipline you w
eren't - you go, out. You were no good. I soon learned that one. I was rather quick at - I'm not boasting but I was quite quick at picking up little bits you know that - were necessary to pick up. I soon found a way to keep 'em quiet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would there be a
ny difference between people who did college training then when they came to be teachers, would they have been paid more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, they were paid more. But they fell into the same category of - if they couldn't keep discipline they were - got rid of. 
I remember two or three out here, came from college, yes, they got the college training, but they could no more - look after a dozen children than they could a dozen - mice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did not having the college training handicap you at all? In terms of promotio
n?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well - yes, you got your increments every year, but then in 19 - 1944 - all this non-college training was done away with. And if you'd done - I think it was twenty years as a non - as a non - twenty to twenty-five, I'm not quite sure which it was,
 you were - classed as - certified. Certificated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go on to evening classes or anything like this after you finished?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well there was no evening classes to go to my dear for years. They started evening classes at the - Weymouth Grammar sch
ool and Weymouth Technical college when that opened I went over there - one or two winters, for - the German language, but not for ordinary subjects. I went away on - reconstruction courses - several times but the - the county offered you to go away to ce
r
tain centres, and take a month's training in this, that or the other. I went for book biding for one month - to - Scarborough. And another time I went for - stick printing. You could go away for courses like that you see for a month at a time. They - you 
paid your own - you paid your own fare. But you paid nothing else. But you gave up your month for an intensive - training you see, in this, that or the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you get paid your salary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, just the same. Oh and basketmaking, I went in for that too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you have any formal teaching then after the age of sixteen, besides being taught how to teach a class? Were you given any further teaching?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. Oh no. But - when I - I - I found that I - could do very well with handwork so I went
 for this book binding class, and then another summer I took - all the the printing had to do with it, and then I took - basket making. That's very fascinating. I liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. I'm sorry that I wasn
't able to go to college. But of course there wasn't the money and therefore I couldn't go. But it would have made a lot of difference to my position - from monetary - point of view. But that's the only reason. Other than that I was happy enough out there
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you think you had the best education possible?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I think I had the best education possible that I could have got in - in Portland - at the time that I was living you see. Oh yes, I think I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it very expensive to go to Miss Love's school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I can't remember the fees, in fact I don't think I ever knew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did it cause much hardship to your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
The music lessons were a guinea a term, I remember that, because I had - I was given a guinea to pay. But I - I can't remember what the - tuition fees were, I really can't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did it cause much problems for your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Not to my - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they able to pay it without much difficulty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
They seemed to be able to pay it without any difficulty. Oh no, I don't think it caused much difficulty. Father was quite well paid I think for the job he was doing see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You say he was actually Target Master, would he have been sort of self employed in the harbour doing this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or was he under somebody?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Government.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 But he would have been like a managerial position?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Well - he was - well, a target was a big wooden frame, that they use before they use - the - the gunnery school. You see, they came into practice firing. Well they didn't use
 - guns - they didn't use - targets - as they use today. They were great big wooden frames. And these were taken out to sea, and then they had - these ships - of course we had all the fleets - the fleet used to come in in big numbers those days, we didn't
 
have one - fleet in, one ship in, we had twenty you see. And they used to go out to sea at night and try and hit these - targets you see. And then they'd come back the next morning all battered up. Well then father'd have to get them mended up and - and b
uilt up again you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would he be actually working on them himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or did he have a work crew under him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh he had a work crew under him. But he did work himself. But he was responsible when they came in, he was responsible for their repair and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Who was his immediate supervisor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Supervisor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Who would he be responsible to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I don't know. I don't remember. I suppose - I suppose he would be responsible to somebody. Captain. Captain I suppos
e. The Captain of the dockyard. I expect he was responsible to the Captain, I really can't tell you. I can't remember. But there was always a Captain down here you see. I think - I think he was responsible to the Captain. There's nobody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 There are so many jobs down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh, now of course, yes. Of course you go back, father died in 1911. But I - I think the Captain was his - superior.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
When abouts in 1911 did he die, do you remember what month of the year it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 June 19th.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And he'd been off work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, he'd been off work for about six months then, because of this poisoned arm you see. The poisoned hand. And then it spread - all over him, this - poison spread. So that his - back and all was affected. Brights disease s
et in. Mm. That was - can't tell you much more can I? Not on my few years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I wanted to ask you a little more about your parents life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 My parents life? Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father take an interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. Well when I say no 
- yes he did to a certain extent, but - was never - I never heard it discussed, I know he was a Conservative. And I know he was very interested when King Edward VII came here. No I think it was VII. Yes it was. King Edward VII came here. Well he was very 
enthusiastic about all that. But - it was never discussed. I never heard it discussed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 With friends at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well he might have done, but - with the visitors we had but - it didn't interest me sufficiently to know that there was - anything being discussed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was your mother at all interested?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mother couldn't have been less interested if she'd tried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father actually belong to the Conservative party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Belonged to the Conservative - club. He was a member of the club I belie
ve. As far as I know. But - I said he didn't go out to take an interest, to - make a - set - time of going to these meetings or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember political meetings going held on the island then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I remember there were - yes, there were p
olitical meetings but - of course I was never taken, I - he didn't take mother, mother didn't go. As I tell you mother was - well she was more interested in her cooking and her home, and keeping the place - I mean those days women didn't take the - intere
st outside the home did they. Well you wouldn't know but - but - unless you were extremes - unless you were an extremist you didn't seem to take any - great interest in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When would your father have gone to the Conservative club then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh of a night. Now and again. Only now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would he have gone once a week or just once a month or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
When the - when the fit took him I should think. Or if he wanted to meet someone special I suppose that's - I don't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would he use it purely as a social club then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. He didn't - no. No, didn't come into it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember your father voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Always. Always - oh yes, had to vote. Mother had to vote. I remember that. I can remember them going to vote. Oh yes, they took their part in that all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother vote for the Conservative party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I think so. Well if your husband did in those days you did didn't you, there was - there was very little - difference 
like there is today. I mean the woman goes to the right and the man goes to the left and there it is. There was more conservatism between people I think - than there is today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he do anything connected with the elections?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he help at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Would he have been a regular attender at the club at this time or have taken very little interest in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Taken very - oh, took an interest, yes, but not - to - to go to - not to put himself out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 In some places men fel
t they risked their jobs and houses if they voted differently from their employers. Was there anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh - no. No, father was in - under government you see so it didn't make any difference. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there much pressure put on people here on 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well years ago there was. Before my time, I understand there was a great deal of pressure, you had to vote for gaffer. That was the head of the quarry. If you didn't vote for Gaffer well you were out, you look out. If you were in the quarry -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would this be local politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Local council sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Or - and also - Parliamentary I suppose, because whatever your gaffer was - or - that's the head of the - quarry, the owner of the quarry I should say,
 well whatever gaffer was you had to be you see if you wanted to keep in with him. That was the old politic of the - island, old politics of the island.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did people tell you about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. And I've read about it. I've read some very old book
s of Portland and - you had to do as gaffer did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would this have been about the 1880's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And further on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And earlier than that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, further - forward.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Nearer 1900?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Yes. Oh yes, whatever gaffer did and what the gaffer said was law.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I haven't come across this actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Haven't you? Yes. But it was - it was among the old families, the Stones and the Flues and the - Cumbans, if you worked in gaffer Samson's quarry, that's one of the big quarry on this here at one 
time, well if you worked in Gaffer Sansom's quarry you did and thought exactly as Gaffer did, you see. 'Cos you had to keep in with him. '{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cos{\*\xmlclose} if not you might get the - thrown out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I haven't come across anybody who worked for him yet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well you s
hall have to - have to be somebody maybe or - or a bit older you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father take any interest in local politics then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh no. He was in the Navy, therefore he - he wouldn't be - in the Court League or have anything to do with the Court
 League. That was mostly the real Portlanders who were interested in Court League and took part in Court League. All quarry owners or - participants of the quarry. He didn't - it wouldn't itself in - anyone from the Navy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And yet the Court League had jurisdiction over this part of Portland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes, but - no, father had nothing to do with that. No. The headmaster I worked for for so many years, out here, he was a member of the Court League, because he was a real Portlander. And he was a 
member of the Court League. You see, it went to Portlanders more than - outsiders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When your father was not at work, how did he spend his time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Woodwork. Yes, he had a workroom you see. He had a proper workroom. One room in the house was made into a workroom. He used to spend all his time woodworking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And his chickens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, and his chickens, yes. He did a lot of fret work - was a great thing in those days. Just - real dust collecting muck. 'Course father took a lot of pride in his - fretwork.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he go out anywhere else besides to the Conservative Club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. Not to my knowledge. He was a real home bird, he would stay at home. Spend his evenings - either sitting down - French polishing or reading - or doing fretwork. Spent hours -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there any social life connected with the dockyard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or with the Navy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he see much of Navy people once he'd left the Navy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, 'cos - no, there was no - social club or anything not - in those days. There is now, but - there wasn't then. There was no social life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about your mother then, did she have any interests outside the home?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Mother was very keep to yourself. She was always either dressmaking or crocheting or - reading to me or teaching me, she taught me to read before I - ever I went to school. Cooking. She did have some friends, but very few. And some of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she go out to see these friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, go - we had great friends in Wyke. Used to go to Wyke a lot, that's the next village on. But - and they came in to her - to here to us. Came in here to us, but - she wasn't a - for going in peoples houses or - gossiping in peoples houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
What would they have done with these friends then? When they spent the evening together would they have a meal together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh - yes, have a meal, come and have a meal or entertain them with cards or - when I was old enough I had to play to everybody and - mind you do it properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were these Naval people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, most - most of th
em were - retired Navy or Naval people you know, in their own circle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your parents regularly entertain friends to meals then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well not regularly. Now and again. Now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Get on with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well they were more - they accepted 
them but they never made - you weren't accepted in the - in - intimate stage, shall we say. There was very little intimacy. We lived between two {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} families. Well - mother and father were quite friendly with them, but I don't remember any intimacy of - relationship between them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would your mother have gone into their houses at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, now and again. But only now and again. But they never - one old lady it was our landlady, lived next door, she was always popping in. She'd open the glas
s, we had a glass door that you could open you see, and - Mrs Dart, Mrs Dart, are you there? Can I come in? Yes, Mrs Pearce, you can come in. Oh I thought I'd come in and talk to you for a few minutes. And a few minutes would perhaps be three hours. And t
hat's - and through her I learnt a lot of Portland customs, and a lot of Portlanders did, through listening to this old lady you see. Mm. I sat still and very quiet and I was taking it all in. She's a funny old soul. Funny old soul.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 But you mentioned the reaction when they first moved here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Mm. Damned well - what was it, bloody well get out - back to your ship out of the way or words to that - you're not wanted here. And the old man who refused to serve her up in the - greengrocers shop, but
 he came round after a while. Oh we used to stand and talk to him for quite a long time, afterwards, when he got used to it you see and more - more - outsiders came forward.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When your parents had friends round for a meal then would your mother have co
oked it all and served it, would you have it in the middle room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well there was no - end room so we had to have it in the middle room. There wasn't - it was - too small, see, so we had to use the middle room you see. Oh yes, there'd be - be cooked or else -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would it be a cooked meal or would it be sort of like a tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well I suppose you'd call it - what today you call a high tea. More that sort of thing you know. Usually finished up with cream and fruit though. The remains of Devon coming ou
t you see. Because mother was a very good cake maker So there was always a - good size - family cake on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did your mother go out then to any meetings other than just to other peoples houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. When the - years ago the Paisley Cornflow
er Company - came to Portland and held a lot of cookery lessons, gave a lot of cookery lessons. Oh mother was there. Mother was there all right. But - there was very little you could go to here because there was no social affairs here you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Very rare. She didn't like the parson. It was a very very old parson here, and in those days - as far as I can remember - if you were church you were church and if you were chapel you were chapel and - that one didn't visit tha
t one, that didn't visit that one. There was too much - well - petty - what shall I call it - don't quite know what to - what word to use for it. Well they seemed to be - so in - ingrate with their own crowd, you weren't wanted. You know, they didn't take
 
you in at all. I don't remember mother taking me to chapel at all. I used to go with the next door neighbours quite a lot. They were - what is now known as Primitive Methodists or Methodists, and they used to come and fetch me and I had to go, because mot
her - would stay home with father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would your mother have gone to church or gone to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I think she was Church of England as far as I know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You went to the Methodist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When I - yes, but afterwards I - joined up with the Church
 - it was con - converted - confirmed - to the Church of England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother go to any church activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. No. Mother never went. I said she was very much a stay at home bird than -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your father take part in any sports at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Not one. He wasn't a sportsman. Nor is his daughter. I'm not interested in sport at all. Because football then - well, in 19 - say - 1900 to 1911, football was - not what it is today by any means. Might be one football match held up at the Grove Corne
r. But - as I said, he wasn't a foot - he wasn't a sportsman at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have any relatives living anywhere near?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. Had no relatives nearer than Portsmouth. Portsmouth and Plymouth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 The only people then you went out to see then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Were friends. Acquaintances. Mm. Made either through the - dockyard, through his work, or else - people - connected with us who lived near. But - no, we had no relatives. We're a very small family you see. Mother only had one brother, and I had no brother
s and sisters. And she lost her brother when he was quite - well - middle aged, and they only had two daughters, but they died - one died very young. So we - we're not a big family at all. There were a few cousins kicking around in Exeter and - Sidmouth b
ut -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What happened then if your mother was ill, how did she manage then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well she - I can only remember her being ill once. And - grandma came, yes, yes, the measles. Only - that's all I remember. I don't remember mother being ill. 'Til she was older. Then her health broke.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about when your father was ill, did she have much help then from anybody?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, the old lady next door was very helpful. And - who was it - oh and there was a - a person living here then, of course she's been dea
d for donkey's years, who was a former - hospital nurse. And if anyone was ill she would go out and help. Well you paid her of course, and mother engaged her when father was so desperately ill. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she just come in by day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh she'd come day or night, whichever you wanted her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did she live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, she'd go home. She lived up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}East Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, she'd go home - to her own home for the night, or - if she was - whenever she wanted to go. She did stay a night or two I believe wh
en father was so desperately ill before he died. But - she was very good. Everybody was after Mrs - Fawcett. Is it - Mrs Fawcett. Now I always remember her, she had such beautiful hair. She had lovely hair and she used to plait it and do it round in a big
 coil. Oh and I admired that - hair, when I was a child. Used to think it was wonderful. Hm. Isn't it funny when you're small how you admire - those kind of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Your mother paid her to come and help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. She'd pay here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I've heard about
 Portland as being very neighbourly and sort of helping each other an awful lot at time in difficulty with washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, if - if you were a Portlander, the Portlanders would help you. But you see were weren't Portland, we were outsiders. And there
fore we weren't included in that circle so much. And of course mother - as I say, mother wasn't one for going out - and mixing a great deal so that - that was another - bit against it. Oh I believe that Portlanders would help each other. But if you were a
n outsider you stayed there you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
People divide society up into social classes and groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to one class or some group and some to others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well yes, I do - I do today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Can you sort of describe the different groups that there were?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well you had - of course in those days there was - some very poor. I mean there was no Social Security for one thing. So you were either very poor or you were middle class or you had mo
ney and you - lived a better life. I think we would come into the middle class. And father had a decent income, a decent living wage. We did very well but there were some of course who were very poor. We lived very well. And - then you had others who had 
much better incomes you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there representatives of each of these classes here on Portland or not?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Representatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there any of what you'd call the top?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, there was a lot - there's - always has been - a lot of money in P
ortland. And of course the quarry owners had the money. 'Cos it wasn't then like it is now split up between Londoners and - groups that called companies, that if you owned a quarry you owned a quarry, and you made some money out of it. Though, of course, 
they were the chief people with money, the quarry owners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Would you put these in the middle class or would you have put them as higher than that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well from the money point of view I'd put them in a higher class. Because money to them was - well money was plentiful. Because the stone sold well you see, but as soon as ever they let the outsiders in and it became a company down it went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 On other grounds would you have put them in the higher class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well yes, they were just ordinary people o
therwise. But they had the money. And therefore they had the - power on the island you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was their way of life very different from say your family's way of life?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Not I shouldn't think so, not a lot, never kept a lot of servants or - they migh
t keep one - servant, but never kept a - big house of servants you know. Nothing like that. But they did have money. They could afford to do differently. And of course as I say Gaffer was looked up to. If you owned a quarry you were somebody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I gather he woned more than one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. Usually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
What other sort of people then belonged in the class that you put yourself in, would they be the shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, some of the shopkeepers, some of the quarry men, who were doing very good business i
n those days, I mean - the quarries were paying good money in those days. So that if you were a quarryman you see you were - well as well off as a business person really. You had - they had their - quarterly what did they call them? Oh. Hm. Can't think of
 the word. Meaning that every so often, money was shared out - amongst them. Now what did they call it? They had a good - no, I can't - can't remember, but the money was shared out you see. And so they were really quite well of some of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of people then would you have put in the lower class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well the labourers. People who laboured - for a living. Whose - income was very very small. What shall we say - the roundsmen of bread and - milk and - people of that - council employees. They wer
e poorly paid in those days. Probably they may not - they may not - they may be - they may have been as good as anyone else, but they hadn't got the money you see, and therefore - they were more or less - looked down upon or kept down. Kept down's a bette
r phrase.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was money the major distinction then do you think on the island?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I think so. Years ago. And if you were a Portlander of course you were included - in far more things than if you were an outsider, if you were a Kinberlan. But - and of co
urse nearly all Portlanders - going back to 1900 - nearly all Portlanders were related. You were either aunts - who were your aunts, who se - thirty-first cousin or something like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would there have been a lot of labouring people then con
nected with the dockyard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. There - there was - quite a lot of people employed in the dockyard who were just labouring people you see. Did - whichever job they were - you were sent in batches to do this or do that. But father had to stick to hi
s targets 'cos he was - that's all he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there many skilled workmen like your father then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, there were some skilled, I men there were - engineers and - oh - metal workers and - people of that class you see. Repairing ships, 'cos ships used to come in to be repaired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did these people live on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Most of them did, yes. A few of them lived in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, but then - it wasn't convenient in those days because there were no buses. You had to depend on the trains, but of cou
rse there were - quite a few trains. I believe the first trains used to come in about six o'clock in the morning. Six or seven o'clock. And go home - well you didn't finish work in those days 'til between five and six. Or six and seven. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did the Navy have much to do with the island or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, not really. They supported the public houses to a great extent. As you always get you see, if you - you had quite a lot of public houses - down near the dockyard. So that the first attraction for the s
ailors when they came to shore - was the - public house. But - they didn't play much part in anything - on the island. 'Cos there was nothing for them to take part in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Would the ordinary people have seen much of the sailors or the officers or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, because the - at one time you see they used to land here - or land - more land here than landed in Weymouth. And of course they come ashore and go to the various parts of the island for their - favourite public house or - well there wasn't 
many clubs here then. Or whatever they wanted. You saw as a many here as you did in Weymouth. And of course fair time, when the fair - when the fair was on old Admiral Beresford, he stopped off Portland - leave in Portland because the sailors got so rough
 
you see. Some of them got so rough so he stopped - I remember that quite well as a child - being told that Admiral - that was the Admiral of the Fleet in those days, Admiral Beresford, he stopped all the - landings in Portland because the sailors got to -
 drunk and so rough. It was really a - a very rough place round Portland fair, in olden days. Especially when the Navy got ashore here between eleven and twelve at night you see was - really rough hooliganism.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go to the fair at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh ye
s, but I was only allowed to go in the - go down in the evening when they took me down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your parents both take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, mother and father would take me down to see what there was. And mother would take me of an afternoon perhaps. But - that was all. When father came home you came home. But it did used to get - a bit on the rough side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
You mentioned Admiral Beresford, presumably he was living in the Admiral's house down there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would he mix much with Portland people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. Admiral Beresford kept himself to himself. He was a very fine man I believe, father was - always speaking very lowly of Admiral Beresford. But - I think he kept his position. No, they would go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} more. Because there were no cars then. They had to go - well yes, there were cars but very very few. I remember the first car that ever seen on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Owned by a man called Lornan, he's dead now of course. He had the first - motor car on the island. And he made a fortune out of it. Made a fortune out of that one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Selling rides, a taxi or something like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well just running a taxi service, you see, for the Navy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Insofar as the
re were certain - children - at school I was forbidden to play with. I mustn't let mother know I played with them. I did but I mustn't let mother know, 'cos - they weren't - clean enough or - they weren't - her social standard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there anybody you had to curtsey to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh no. No. Oh that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or show respect to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, I never curtsied to anybody. That was before my time. And you see, this wasn't a place for - what's the word I want now - well - you didn't go into service, in this place b
ecause there wasn't people - with enough money or big enough houses to employ - servants, who would do the curtseying, perhaps, but I never - came into that - never had anything to do with that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How were you expected to behave towards the Admiral or t
owards people of that rank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Don't know 'cos I never - was never taken in front of them. Suppose I'd have had to sit still and behave myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Do you remember anybody sort of showing respect to your parents in these ways at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 There was a
 set of cottages, we weren't living - well we weren't living far from here then, it was in - over in High Street, there was a set of cottages behind us where there was some - poorer people and - they always - spoke to mother very nicely. And mother used t
o
 help quite a few of them. 'Cos when we had the - fowls, we had so many of these Buff Orpingtons, mother - it was nothing for mother to go and give one of them a dozen eggs. That was a common thing. We had too many for our own use and she'd give - there w
a
s one - party down I remember called Pevett, they were poor, mother used to think nothing to give them a dozen eggs. Another family called Russell I remember very well. Very nice people in themselves but they hadn't got the means. It was nothing for mothe
r to give them a dozen eggs. And that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Who would you have considered the most important people here on 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Most important? Well I suppose the quarry owners. They had the money you see, and if anything was started, well it was always those people who started it or - had a big hand in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there anybody of comparable level down here in Underhill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Of similar sort of standing down here in Underhill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You'd have to go to Cas - you'd have to
 go to Castletown for the - Naval residences then you see. There was the Naval residences down there, even when I was a child. There's one for the Captain in charge, there was one for the next one, one for the Chief Engineer and - so on. Those would be th
e people next.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Were there any civilians with this sort of standing with businesses, shipping businesses or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, in Castletown. Yes, there was the Cox family for one, they did a lot of foreign shipping business. What was the
 other one called. Hm. I've forgotten now. But they did - a lot of - shipping business, dealing with other countries and the ships would come in here and load and unload and - they had dealings with them you see, buying and selling. But they lived mostly 
at Castletown then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was there a big distinction between Castletown and Underhill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they separate communities then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well I suppose in a way, yes, if you lived at Castletown you knew the - the brokers and the - ship people. Ther
e wasn't a great number living in Castletown in those days. There was one or two shopkeepers down there and there would be these - shipping brokers and shipping people, but other than that very few. Most people lived up in the town or - Tophill or -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did the shopkeepers associate generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or keep to themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh no, they associated generally, yes. Took part in what was going on I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about people like the clergymen and doctors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well Doctor Howard was the - doc
tor here then. Well - Doctor Howard - they would open things or - attend things in - in their right. He was a dear old Scotsman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How would people have behaved towards the doctor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh doctor was law. Whatever the doctor said was right. He was a go
od doctor mind, a very good doctor, but he had no time - if you didn't do what you were told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What did your parents think of doctors then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh well mother thought a lot of doctor Howard. Doctor Howard couldn't do a thing well then nobody could. T
here was only the one Underhill then, I forget the name of the man that was on the Top, but Doctor Howard - he had a big practice and of course - poor old chap had to walk everywhere 'cos there was no cars then. I can see him now going up High Street with
 
his hands behind his back. He never rode a bike. He married - he married a Scots girl much younger than himself. But - Tommy - Tommy Howard, everybody spoke of him as Tommy Howard. Tommy Howard - walked up the hill, never hurry up the hill. He warned my m
o
ther against that years ago. Never hurry up the Hill Mrs Dart. 'Cos mother was fly tear when mother went out. You know, she walked very quickly. He was always warning her against - hurrying up the hill. And he always walked very slowly himself up the hill
. Oh he was a good doctor, his surgery used to get packed full. Door old Tommy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, I don't think so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you think she noticed differences?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh with some p
eople she wouldn't - she'd speak to them all if they spoke to her she'd speak, she'd acknowledge everybody, but she wouldn't mix with some of them. Especially the Chiswellites. There were some beautiful - families down there. Hm. Real - if you lived in Ch
i
swell you was considered to be the scum of the island you know, that type. Mm. If you lived in Chiswell you were - you'd had it. There were some - pretty bad families down there in those days. Hard working some of them but - they had to live there because
 
of course everybody else - it was so cheap to live there. The houses were old and they were cheap, so they had to live there. It was always considered that - if you lived in Chiswell well you weren't quite as good as the rest you know. It was the slum of 
the island, I - we'll put it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
What sort of jobs would they do, would they be people who were working or not working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh there was very little unemployment in those days. You either worked in the quarries or you worked in the dockyard or 
you worked for the business people here on the island, or you worked for the council you see. No there's very little unemployment. Everything was badly paid, but there was employment. If you liked to take it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would these only be very very large families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes, most of them had large families. I remember one family we had in school - called - Silna, yes. They had sixteen children. Another family I remember living in Bidhope had eleven. So they sat down to meals like - this is true - they sat down t
o meals in relays. The rooms weren't big enough, and the table wasn't big enough, so - one lot had their meal and they ran out to play and the other lot came in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of job would their father have had then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I don't remember, I think Mr Smi
th was a quarryman. And he'd be a labouring quarryman. And I think - oh I don't know what the Flans did. I don't know what the Flan family did. But it was very - they were very poor mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would the fishermen have been included in this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, t
he fishermen - most of the fishermen lived down there you see because it was near the sea there in Cove Cottages. Cove Cottages is that terrace going along down here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they considered part of this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 They would be considered part of it you se
e. Of course their living was very poor in those days. There wasn't the - there wasn't the contracts for - fish that there is now. You couldn't make a fortune out of fishing in those days, as you can now. We've got a fisherman living in this terrace, well
 - they can afford a house of this type and - the son - never done anything but fishing. The family of three lives on his earnings. 'Cos all the fish goes in - we get no {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} fish now, it all goes away you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 This is Mr Glaper is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Galpen, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I want to try and see him sometime if I can.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
But don't try and see the old man. Because he'll do nothing for you. If you want to see anybody ask for Mr Derek Galpen. The son. The old man's a sinner. He's a sinner. Miserable old type he is.
 He'll soon turn round and tell you to go to hell as he would answer you. But the son is more - get a table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember him as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Old Mr Galpen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I knew him as a young man. He was a smart man when he was young. They liv
ed on the beach, in a cottage down on the beach. But he's deteriorated terribly. He's got three sisters on the island, they're really smart women. They've married and - they're really smart women. But this one is - really is a - he treats his wife abomina
b
ly. I'm very sorry for her. Though if you want to - learn anything of - fishing or anything like that, ask for - Mr Derek - Galpen. Or ask for - now who is the other family, Whites. Brown. There's a Brown family's got - have two or three boats down there,
 and two or three brothers in - the fishing trade. Now they'd help you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I'm looking for somebody whose father was in the fishing trade 1900-ish.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, well they've all gone, they're dead.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 There's not many around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No there isn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 The only one I could find is Mr Galpen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well, Derek Galpen is - thirty - I suppose he's thirty-eight or nine. But I - I - and the Browns would help you I expect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 They're still fishing down there now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. They're a lot better that family from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Spring{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Gardens{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newton{\*\xmlclose} - if you can go down on the beach and find a 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newton{\*\xmlclose} - ask for Mr Newton, there's - two brothers I think in the fishing trade down there called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newton{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. Now they would be able to help you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it possible at this time when 
you were a child to move from one class to another do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well I suppose it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Do you remember any instances of children who you grew up with getting better jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Getting on in the world? Yes, some of them did, I don't - I remembe
r some of them who - when they left school got into jobs and got on, more than their parents ever did. But most of them - came from homes where - the parents had money, and were able to advance their children. Most of them. And - yet there are some of the
m
 you see - there's a family coming to live next door to us, at the end of this month, I remember them as poor as church mice. They've gone on in the world, one can give ten thousand for a bungalow, the other one's giving eight thousand for this one. They'
v
e got on. But don't ask me how. But they were really very poor. You see - we have the key of the next house for a week or two, and - they came here one night and - one of them said, do you remember me, and I said, yes, I remember you. She said, remember m
e
 as being very poor don't you? I said, yes, I do. Well, she said, I've got on. But she didn't tell me how. But she's got on. And she can give - she's divorced it's true, she can give ten thousand for a bungalow. Which - you must have made money to be able
 to do that mustn't you. You can't - start taking up for a bungalow of ten thousand if you haven't go something behind you. No. Oh yes, some families have got on very well, and have - risen consequently, have risen into a different - circle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you rem
ember this ever happening within the one generation, of the father being able to improve his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Not - no. Some went into business and improved then in many cases the youngsters went away. And got on, they - went to London for study or went to - col
lege here or college there and improved themselves and got on in that way. But there - was no such thing as getting on in that way in Portland you see, you had to go out of the island.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of families would they have come from, the children to 
go away like this to college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh from - from decent families.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would this be the business peoples children again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Business people or people - quarry people you see, who had made a bit of money. Or had - shares in the quarry. People like tha
t. I remember one family living along the lane there - father was in the quarries, well he had shares in the - the quarries you see. Well his two sons went to London and got on remarkably well. But you had to go out of the island to get - any position rea
lly. Because there was nothing here to get a position in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did Portlanders value education then as a means of getting on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Some of them did. But some men would term it their book learning. They would talk in those days. Their book learning. OE dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Do you remember any instances of mobility the other way? With on one generation of a family going down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. I don't remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Father being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, because there was no unemployment, or very little unemployment, but - and i
f there was unemployment it was because of the - well - so called classes mostly you see. There was no - unemployment as I can remember, amongst the ordinary people here. It was something unknown in those days. It isn't now but - it used to be. I don't re
member any of my schoolfriends having their fathers unemployed. No. That would have been a disgrace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember seeing a policeman around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes. Oh yes, of course I do. Policemen always about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What did you think of the policeman at that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
They didn't worry me. I had no reason to be worried of the policemen, but you saw the policemen walking about the streets those days you see, there was no cars or - saw a policeman walking about up and down Fortuneswell. Down the dockyard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of relationship did he have with the community?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Quite good I think. Except for those who - had to - to shun him. Oh yes, the police - we had a fairly big police force here. Then of course there was the Metropolitan police - who lived - inside the dockyard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 They actually lived in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 There was - special quarters for the Metropolitan police.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You said your father was quite friendly with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 He was quite friendly, yes, he used to visit with the police all right. 
The Metropolitan police. But - oh to see a policeman walking about was a common thing. He was as common as the lamplighter in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it considered to be a good job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes. Although most of the policemen I can remember here had big families. But it was considered quite a decent job. They had bikes, but they had no walkie-talkies and they had no cars.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were they considered as an important member of the community then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well yes. Be a policeman, you're quite an important member of the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was he looked up to then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 More or less. I can remember quite a few of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Do you remember did your mother ever say to you anything like I'll call a policeman if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No. That was something unknown. Tell your father - i
f you don't behave yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did mother's use this threat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I don't know my dear, I couldn't tell you. My mother never used it to me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 In some places I think they were feared almost because of this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. But I don't suppose I would have
 been you see because we used to have these Metropolitan policemen here in - in their civvies and I knew they were policemen. I don't suppose it would have frightened me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did they come here to your house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, those Metropolitan, father used to bring them home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 With their families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, most of them were single men. And father used to - they used to come up and - have supper or - spend an evening you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When there was somebody in the district who people disapproved of very stro
ngly was there any special way they showed it here on Portland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh I don't know. They kept to their own little group more or less. There were occasions, in villages in particular for instance when people were made to leave by what they used to call rough music.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. They made effigies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. Well I don't remember anything like that here. I don't remember anything of it anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Considerable public pressure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. No, I don't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I think this applies more to rural districts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 To the villages, yes. No I don't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I've been told quarrymen actively working against other families.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh I suppose they did exist, yes, in the quarries, if - quarrymen - was considered - not - their particular class they would be down on him. But I wasn't in the quarry - fraternity - to know much about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I wondered if you ever saw anything like this going on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were there many books in your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes. YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your parents read a lot?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
My mother read a lot, my father read a lot, and I was made to read. I had me - comics. Although of course comics were of a different type than they are now. But I had my comic every week and mother - mother brought - a lot of books with her when sh
e came to Portland, she had a lot of - books of her own childhood. And she'd kept them of course like people used to do years ago, so they were handed to me and was - taught to read them. And they were most - if I remember rightly they were mostly - quite
 
nice little stories for children you know. And I was given - those big books called Chatterbox - annuals. Given those and other - fairly big books. But I always liked reading. I was made to read - when I was quite young. I've always liked reading, if I st
ick my head in a book now I rather do that than do anything else. I still like reading. Although I don't approve of all the - modern writers but - I like reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 What sort of things did your father read then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh - newspapers. We always took - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did he have a daily newspaper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. I can't remember what it was called. Chronicle. Chronicle I believe. Well then - mother and father always took Answers, that was - that's off the market now I believe. A book called Answers, and he got ano
ther weekly book called Pearsons, I can see the thing now, Pearsons with a pink cover, bright pink cover, Answers was the bright orange cover with black, and then we had Tit-Bits. A green cover with - black - lettering. Oh we had quite a lot of books comi
n
g in. - our house every week. And then mother used to take a womans book called Home Chat. And then I forget - what's the other one she took? Home Chat. There's another one. Answers, Pearsons and Tit-Bits, that came in every week. When I was a child, that
 
was - looked forward to those and I was allowed to read those. And we had Home Chat. Oh and she - of course being a dressmaker she always took Woman's - Fashions. Always had Rolands every month. It came out monthly in those days so - we always had Weldons
. I can't remember any others. Oh yes, we had quite a lot of - weekly things, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother carry on reading to you after you'd learnt to read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Not so much. No, I - I used to read meself then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Some families would sit round while somebody read and they would all listen.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No, I don't remember mother reading to me not so much. She would now and again perhaps. She'd read the comic to me because - I didn't get on so well reading comics as I did reading ordinary books. I can remember he
r reading me - Scrups. That was my comic, Scrups. It was about the size of a Daily Mirror. And about as many pages in it. I think it was only a penny a week, if I remember rightly. A lot for nothing you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember any other outings with yo
ur parents, apart from going to other peoples houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your parents take you out to see places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well no, because there was no means of going. You see there was no - charabanc - you could go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and go on the - a horse d
riven charabanc if you like, and go out to places. I remember mother taking me out on those once or twice. But - you see there was no trips like there are today. No coach trips or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would your parents have taken you into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} quite a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well usually - usually with mother, father wasn't very fond of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But - oh I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 quite a lot as a child. But there were no - organised outings or trips as there are today. I mean at Sunday schools they all go outside now don't they, to Bournemouth or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Poole{\*\xmlclose}
, well in those days you had your - you walked round the streets singing hymns. That was something, and the - somebody - the piano was put in a - now I did have a photograph of that, but I don't know what's become of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Do you remember that, did you go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Yes. And - you took your own mug with you. I remember going - I can only remember about twice though. And then they put the piano in a - cart, horse driven ca
rt, drawn cart, and somebody sat up there and you stopped at various places, and sang hymns. Walked all round the island 'til you were dead tired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would this be a special time of the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Summertime. Sunday school outing, your Sunday school out
ing or your - anniversary, yes. This was the outing. Walking round the streets singing hymns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would there have been a tea at the end of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Tea at the end, yes. Dough buns. Because Portland dough buns of course you know they're - very - but then
 they weren't like they are now. They weren't little tiny - dough buns about that square. They were nice big ones. Nice big dough buns. And they had - plenty of currants in them in those days and they were made with lard. Pigs lard. Not this American stuf
f. It was all pure pigs lard. Local mostly. And they were really worth eating. But they're rubbish you buy today, well - pitch it over the quarry it would bounce I'm sure.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Were you ever taken out on picnics or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. My mother d
idn't like picnics. And I was never very keen. I went to when I was invited by other children to - some picnics, but it - they never appealed to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How about times like Bank Holidays? Would you have done anything then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No, my parents never went
 anywhere Bank Holidays. Other people did but we never did much anywhere. Well you see went away - usually went home Christmas, and we went home again - at Easter. And I was usually sent to Portsmouth for a - part of my summer holiday, that there was no n
eed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You were sent as part of the summer holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, sometimes I went - I was sent to grandma's you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go on your own then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh no, they took me of course. Well you wouldn't allow a child in those days - I was taken home to stay with grandma for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would your parents come back here and leave you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
They'd come back and fetch - they'd come back and leave me there you see. Then come and fetch me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Would this be for two week or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Someth
ing like a fortnight or three weeks, yes. I think mother was glad to get rid of me. Well she was never fond of children you see. And I think she was - she rather liked me to go away. Oh she'd come and fetch me and - treated me all right but - I got the fe
eling that - she was glad to pass me on to somebody else. And I didn't mind being passed on I might tell you. Because I was very fond of my grandmother. There's nobody in the world - if I had to choose between mother and grandma, mother - grandma.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You 
mentioned that you belonged to the Sunday school, would you have gone every Sunday afternoon to Sunday school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, for - several years I did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 How old were you when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh, somewhere about nine I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 'Til you were about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh 'til I was really a big girl. I used to go to chapel with these - neighbours next door.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was that morning, afternoon or evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh chapel, it was only go in the evenings, didn't - my father took good care I practiced - Sunday mornings. I had to play to him all - the pieces I should play properly. If you can't play them properly you go and practice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Were there any other regular aspects of Sunday, routines like this on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. I don't think so. We always went out Su
nday evenings if it was fine. Father and mother and we were taken for long walks all round the top of the hill, South well and - Weston and Ware and Wigwam. I got then I knew the history - I knew the geography I should say of Top Hill thoroughly. That -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 And in the wintertime would you have done this
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well not in the wintertime so much you see of course, you - you'd stay in and play, play games or you played - the piano when you were old enough or you - you read your books or - you did your crochet or whatever you were doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Was there any other aspect of Sunday school, you say they had this one outing on anniversary, did they have anything at Christmastime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Well I never went see because never here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Sports or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Don't remember. Sports were - when they had the Sunday school treat there were sports in the field. But I don't remember any other sports.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 This was when you went round singing in the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm. Yes. Muggings didn't take any part in the sports because she hated it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you belong to a choir then at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. I hadn't got a voice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you belong to any other clubs connected with the church, there were things like the Girls Friendly Society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes, no, I didn't go to any of t
hat. There was Band of Hope. And - Girls Friendly Society, no, I - no, I was never in any of that. The only club I ever belonged to was when - oh - the last twenty years that would be, I belonged to the Business and - Business and Professional Womens Club
.
 I belonged to that for - oh - about ten years. I was president of that for twelve months. They wanted me to take it on for two years but I wouldn't do it. I only took it on for a twelve month and then I'd had enough. Then I came out of that through illne
s
s, when I was - ill when I left school I came out. That was all right, but - I mean that was all right, but there was more business than there was professional about it. The way the business people got into it - they - we had very few professionals, there
 was a few - head teachers, a couple of head teachers and myself and - one or two others. Hospital people. But there was more business people in it than anything. And we had to have the club -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go to any theatres or to any concerts as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. Because there's none to go to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Anything in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Weymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I wasn't taken anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Or to the cinema? There was a cinema down in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well if you like to call it so. If you like to call it so but - the common name for it was the bug hutch. No, I wasn't allowed to go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you in fact hear any music then, you were taught the piano, did you ever see any recitals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well yes, on the gramaphone, father had a gramaphone you see so we had some good records.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was that the only time you ever really heard -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
But that was the only time I heard real good music. Because there was nothing here you see. Well there was one - was one - society on the hill, but then you had to get to Top Hill for that. Again, you see, there
 was no buses then when I'm talking about. So you had to walk.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go to anything up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 When you were older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well I was never allowed out much you see, my mother and father didn't agree with me going out alone. Although father died when I was - sixteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
How about that period after your father died when you were teaching as a monitor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
What sort of things did you do in your leisure then? Did you go out at all in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Very little. I did a
 lot of fancy work. Spent hours and hours doing fancy work of all kinds. Oh mother and I went out occasionally, we - used to go to - oh we went to some - yes - there was a - quite a nice group of - whist drives held here. Run by the Navy. And I've gone - 
went to quite a lot of whist drives when I was a youngster, well, say in the teens and - sixteen to twenty, somewhere like that. Well the occasional concert we'd go to if there was one available.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Where would these be held then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh perhaps in one 
of the chapels or - there was no other - or if there was some visiting artist might come to the Masonic hall. I would go then. But there wasn't a great deal to go to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you belong to any societies or groups at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. No. No. 'Cos there wasn't very much to belong to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Did you spend your Sunday differently then? Did you still go to church or chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 No. I didn't go then. Spend my Sunday oh reading or - writing or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you take an interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 I was never ve
ry keen. I suppose I'm more keen now, I take more interest - in my latter years than I did when I was a youngster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you make any new friends at this sort of stage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh yes, people I was working with at school, we were friendly and - used to c
ome to the house occasionally and - I'd go to theirs, well they were mostly outsiders so - but - oh yes, I made friends then and you see I've lost all those, they're nearly all dead or - several of them went abroad when the first world war - came, they we
n
t abroad with - Australian men and married and - no, I can't find - they've nearly all died. Only this week I heard of one go that I was very friendly with. Married in the first world war, married a Lieutenant Commander, went off to Ramsgate. Well you gra
dually drifted apart you see, they - she had a business up there, and we lost contact with them and I heard this week that she'd died suddenly, that's another one gone. No, they're all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you go out to dances or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Never danced.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Was it that you didn't want to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Well partly that I didn't want to and partly mother was - against it. I never - was very keen, I never wanted to go. I think it was rather silly - now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have any boyfriends at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Yes.
 Had a boyfriend. And he was killed in the first world war. And that was the end of that. He was - he was really an intelligent man too. He kept - his mother and father kept a shop up in the town. And he really was a brilliant scholar. But he was killed i
n the first world war. Doing - would have been - I suppose held a good position if he'd lived, because he was so brilliant. And that's - that's how life goes on. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did you have friends into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes, now - now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Did your mother mind you having friends in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
Oh - it was only a - I wouldn't make a - lot of fuss, well we couldn't afford to spend too much. Of course - the first world war you see, you couldn't entertain because your - your rations were so small, yo
u couldn't do much with it. And the second world war was nearly as bad. What can you do with one ounce of butter a week. That's what we were getting in the first world war you see, one ounce of butter a week. Well - what can you do with it? And so -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 You were a bit older now at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13984790 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
I'm thinking of when you were about sixteen, seventeen, eighteen, whether you went out more at that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14892304 FD  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7831280\charrsid7023924 
No. Mother was a widow you see and I didn't go out a great deal. 'Cos mother was a w
idow when I was fifteen. No, I - I don't remember going out a great deal. If I did she went - she - I - I took her out. More or less you see. And then when the war came on you see my - boyfriend - went to war, he was called up, quite a kid. Went away and 
got killed in France. That was the end of that. You smile about it now but - it wasn't smiling - smiling matter then. Because that was a waste of a good life. He was really - a brilliant scholar. All wasted you see.
